,Recommended,251570,12677010,"Posted: 28 October, 2014",all,Blood Flowers,"(Updated for A13.6)7 Days To Die (7DTD) is not a truly ""unique"" game, but that is, in fact, one of the greatest things about the game. It blends the best parts of many games (the building from Minecraft, the open-world aspect of Skyrim, the terrifying zombies of... etc) and makes them its own. For instance, while Minecraft building uses grids and is unrealistic, 7 Days To Die takes that, adds gravity and dynamic changes while retaining all the fun.One of the first things you will notice about 7DTD is that the graphics are surprisingly high definition. Granted it takes a pretty intense system to utilize higher graphical settings, for a ~$20 game that often goes on sale, the graphics are superb. Even on the lowest settings the game looks incredibly realistic.Then come the zombies. Depending on your settings, these guys go from terrifying to downright unstoppable. You think you're safe behind your walls? Not when they rapidly bash their way through. You think they won't come for you as long as you stay quiet? Not when the feral horde comes seeking your blood. The zombies are made to punish the unprepared survivor and they do it extremely well. Of course, there is not just a single static zombie type. You have police officer zombies that launch projectile attacks, zombie dogs that will viciously run you down, zombie hornets that are just plain annoying, and zombie bears - yes, you did read that correctly, zombie bears.7DTD is challenging for the new survivor, it is made to punish the player during the early game. You are affected by the temperature (you can actually freeze to death), you require sating of both hunger and thirst, and there are more things that can kill you that you can possibly count (including falling trees). Yet, as you get further into the game and explore further into the world, there is a sense of reward and accomplishment that accompanies the hard earned experience. You begin to harvest raw materials faster, craft stronger tools and weapons, build more fortified bases, etc. Eventually, it is no longer you who needs to run from the zombies, but the zombies who need to run from you.My two favorite aspects of 7DTD blend nicely together: crafting and building. I have not seen a (similar) game that has as extensive a selection of craftable items as this one. There are tons of items to craft and then use to build into castles, homes, crazy-spiky fortresses, or whatever you wish really. In a game where everything is destructible, you are also capable of building anything your heart desires. What you make depends on what strikes your fancy. If you want to create something grand, build an epic castle. If you want to create something that will withstand a sea of zombies, then layer spikes and walls and, of course, ever more spikes.While all of these features are great in singleplayer (honestly, you can play hundreds of hours in singleplayer without getting bored), the ultimate fun in this game comes from playing with others. Get a group of friends and play on insanely hard settings while trying to survive from heat-seeking, running zombies. If you don't have any friends (amumu...), you can still go on multiplayer servers to join up with or against other players!In conclusion, 7DTD is simply a lot of fun. You get out of it whatever you want. You can be a survivor, you can be an architect,and heck - you can even try and be a pacifist (VERY hard). Whether you choose to play alone, play with strangers, or play with friends, you'll find yourself losing countless hours in senseless fun. I highly recommend buying 7 Days To Die - it's worth every cent."
