76561197999909435,Recommended,251570,14349995,"Posted: 6 February, 2015",all,Dan,"I'm writing this review after clocking a good amount of playtime and hope mylengthyreview can be of some use to new/current/veteran/potential players. It's always good to start with the good:THE PROSThis game is the love-child of The Walking Dead (TV show) and MinecraftRelatively friendly interface and easy-to-play (a contradiction noted in theTHE CONS)Great sandbox experience; allowing players to adopt any playstyle they choose would suit them in the apocalypse: hoarder, scavenger, murderer, good samaritan.. with amazing potential for roleplay experience!Huge list of craftable weapons whether they be melee or firearms; each with their own advantages.Huge list of craftable materials which can be used to manipulate a fully functional envrionment (if you see it, you can destroy it)Good balance between ""risk/reward"" and ""time spent in-game/achievement""Great modding options for setting-up servers to suit your playstyleTHE CONS- The majority of which are experienced in multiplayer games.This is Alpha. Be careful if you choose to buy/play this game. It is riddled with bugs/glitches/cheats/hacks.Complaining or asking for help on official forums in relation to multiplayer games, will be met with:""This is alpha"", ""Go play single-player"", ""This is alpha!"", ""Join a server with your friend"", ""THIS IS ALPHA!""Unfriendly interface for joining multiplayer games. I still have no idea what some of those 'filter' options mean/do and there is nothing in-game that explains them; not even on the wiki or offical website.Anti-cheat system doesn't workFrustratingly annoying to connect directly to a friend's game. Port-forwarding, etcNo option to ""type only to friends"" or ""private whisper"" in-game. All typing is global.Relatively slow updates from the devsRocket launchers, advanced military sniper rifles and fully-automatic machine guns *sigh* (A personal ""con"" for me, as it destroys the immersion of a zombie apocalypse)Single player soon becomes extremely tedious/pointless.Known Cheats/ExploitsNo-clip. Players can shoot through walls, floors, etc.Duplicate items. Players can stack/duplicate items.Track bedroll. Players can track another player's base after he/she places a bedroll.Invisible killing. Players can attack another player from anywhere on the map.Flying.Item spawning.Despite there being moreCONS, thePROSsignificantly outweigh them.Hope this helps. I strongly recommend this game. Buy it."
76561198089209418,Recommended,251570,8546007,"Posted: 3 January, 2014",all,NEGA SCOTT,"EDIT: 6/21/2015So, I've now played through every update, put in about 200+ hours through this and my other steam account, (Teknospawn), this one being my smurf account, and I wanted to explain EXACTLY what you can expect if you buy this game. This is going to be a mostly fact based review of what you will experience, and it will be up to you to decide if you will like it. I will also post this same review on my other steam account.1) The game has been in alpha for a VERY long time and it will most likely stay that way for at least the next year or so. However they do have a daily updated developer page that posts exactly what they are doing:http://joelhuenink.tumblr.com/2) The game is ""mostly"" finished in that even in it's current state, it feels like a ""complete"" game. It rather feels like they continue to release new free ""DLC"" content every other month.3) If you're looking for the best graphics quality, you will not find it here. However the graphics are good enough for a voxel based sandbox game, in my opinion. The graphics never take away from the feel of surviving and dominating an apocalyptic world and with the Unity 6 upgrade, it's gotten better.4) Although you will die A LOT in the beginning until you understand the game mechanics, the zombie element will eventually become easy, and the human combat is what you will have to watch out for. As the days accumulate the zombies become progressively harder.5) The game definitely ""feels"" like you're trying to survive an apocalyptic wasteland. The growing curve is not too bad, after you've put in about 10+ hours to understand how to survive and use the 7daystodie crafting wiki, you begin to feel like you have control over your environment. All in all, if you want to master surviving, fighting, crafting, and build a huge kick♥♥♥♥♥base, it will take you a total of 100+ hours to get there. In my opinion, although you can continue to play more, this game is worth about a 100+ hours of fun. So for the price, I think it's worth it. Although I play dota 2, which is free and I've played dota 1 + 2 a combined amount of about 10,000 hours.Now on to exactly what the game contains based on how you will experience it for the first time.You start off by spawning in a general area near a ""hub city"" where everyone spawns near. This city will have tons of low level stuff to loot to get you started including tools, food, resources, materials, weapons, etc.. If you want to know exactly what you can craft, go to:http://7daystodie.gamepedia.com/CraftingIf you're on a busy server, you'll need to travel further out in order to be safe from players and find less actively looted spots.In the beginning you will have to sneak around a lot of zombies, eat a lot of plants and animals to survive, and basically be a super noob, just to not die. I suggest finding a cave, and building a small easily defended starter house in it. You will experience a lot fear and death for the first few hours until you get the hang of it, or get lucky and come across someones existing base which has become inactive because the player quit that server. In that case  you will start with a plethora of items and will live like a king for a few days.However, unless you're playing on a PVE server, you must ALWAYS be careful for other high level players who are running around trying to kill everyone on the server, so building an underground base is best for noobies.The next few days will be pretty much exactly like minecraft. Learning to build structures, learning to build resources and making better versions of each as you go. Building a defensive outdoor structure will be the next big step. How you want to create this ingenius zombie proof castle is up to you, but be warned your tools dull down and break. Ammos is quickly spent. Feral zombies can detect your fire's heat signature. Spider zombies can climb up walls, and call forth a horde of zombies if they spot you directly. Zombie dogs will run faster than you, some zombies will crawl and break your legs, others will spit explosive puke grenades to destroy your building. But if you hide successfully enough, people will still come around and be♥♥♥♥♥♥♥and kill you.But once you've survived for a few weeks, you should be rich as $hit and able to build a massive and well built mansion for which you can live out the rest of your days honing your building skills. Zombies will no longer be a challenge. People will still be a challenge, but build far away enough and it won't be necessary to be extremely defensive. (I personally play on a PVE server so that I can just focus on building.)As for building, the gravity challenge makes building realistic structures fun. It's not like minecraft where you can just put block on block on block. Each block can hold only so much weight before it comes crashing down. Make your foundational blocks strong, and build on those. You would be suprised what you can build with proper planning and strategy. I personally think the buliding part is the best part of 7daystodi.Once you've mastered the game, much like minecraft, it now becomes about what you can build through your honed skills. If you don't enjoy the challenge of building, then this game is not for you, as the zombies don't create much of a challenge for someone who has survived for a few days on one server.All in all this game to me, is the best ""updated"" basic minecraft building game with better graphics, and more surviving and I still play it to this day."
76561198062297836,Recommended,251570,15552303,"Posted: 25 April, 2015",all,EnterName,"This game's crafting options turned me into a DIY nut.  Early game was spent by a riverside shack I created right next to a river in the forest biome.  I surrounded it with corn, cotton, maple tree, blueberry and potato farms.   Absolutely zero protection, but I was relatively safe during the night in sneak mode at the top of my 4 block high 7x7 abode wielding my handmade crossbow.  Had a hell of a time trying to find all the books I'd need for crafting, particularly the one that would allow me to build a forge.  Luckily, I found a cooking pot pretty easily (I know from previous playthroughs how screwed you are when you can't boil your own water).  Lived off boiled meat very early, but before long I was making a living baking potatos.Mid-game, I set up mining operations near my shack mining for stone,lead, iron, coal and potassium nitrate at night, while the hordes passed overhead (mostly) unawares.  During the day, I hunted, hit supply drops and did some supply runs on hardware stores and the homes nearby.  Stocked up a lot of rebar frames and wood frames plus came across a lot of tools from the hardware store runs.  I saved the rebar frames for later, and used the wood frames as fuel for my cooking and forge fires so I could stockpile wood from my maple tree farm.   Ended up with a metric ton of animal fat between hunting and those slow bloater zeds, the little I needed to make candles barely made a dent in my stock.  Used the corn to make cornmeal, then that to make clay.  With the clay and my supply runs, I was able to make molds of all parts of every firearm in the game.Late-game: prepared to make the defensible, self-sustainable lair of my dreams.  40 x 40, four block high walls topped with barbed wire that are three blocks thick using stone from mining to make concrete (outer layer is reinforced concrete, using the rebar frames from runs; inner two were simple concrete).  Surrounded by a 3 block deep moat with sharpened tree trunk traps at the bottom.  Entrances on the north, south, east and west sides secured with two metal doors each.  Inside, I had enough room to rebuild all my farms, all my forges and cooking fires, a mine, and built a two story house in the center.  Have a small lake for water.  Now, pretty much the only reason I would HAVE to venture out is to hunt to maintain my stores of animal fat and venison (fat for biofuel and candles, venison for venison stew, which is awesome) and ironically, sand.  I use the sand to make glass jars because the game, inexplicably, does not allow you to keep jars after you use water for anything other than drinking (like making venison stew or grain alcohol, which I use with biofuel to make my own gas cans for power tools).  Between the iron I've mined and continute to, and the molds I have, I'm able to build any number of guns.  Between lead, coal, potassium nitrate and a stockpile of brass (you should really be able to mine this too) I can make any bullet.  Have plenty of books for shotgun shell wadding.That was just one way to go about it.  You can be a nomad packing it up during the day and raiding any town or muni building you see.  Or you can fortify an existing structure and save on building resource cost.  What's most surprising to me is how a game that is in early access, which has made no attempt at a storyline (so far) can really make you ask yourself how you would survive an apocalyptic scenario.  Highly recommended, especially if they come through with the dirtbike they said they'd include in the game.  Would make late-game looting really fun for the stay-at-home types."
