76561197977820099,Recommended,251570,25896060,"Posted: 6 October, 2016",all,Lizzard,"Not enough of this is usually said about games that are actually doing OK, so here's one. Keep it up Pimps! :)I played the game years ago in its earliest builds; it was a train wreck. For all the complaints the game gets now, people would have had a stroke if they had played it back then! Zombies spawned on your head and blocks were these wavy things that never lined up the way you wanted them to, giving the entire game a sort-of Tim Burton feel, cars blew up if zombies walked on them and you could find a sniper rifle within the first 5 minutes of playing at times.Years later, you'd be amazed at how much progress this game has made, especially to others in the genre. This is my ""go to"" game when comparing others I play to it and I don't think people fully appreciate everything this game brings with it, to the table.For one, the graphics are good. Not great, but definitely not bad, especially for a non-AAA title. You could basically run this game on a potato (like I initially did) and still get a great gaming experience out of it.The crafting is a step above most and/or has kept up with what people expect it to be and has definitely been made better over the years. I somewhat recall the earlier crafting to be a bit of a mess. When they ""dumbed-down"" the recipes to incorporate bulk items such as generic ""wood"" instead of half a dozen versions of wood, it felt like crafting became a lot more intuitive.Terraforming. This game has it, many do not. There may be lots of titles out there, but a lot lack the basic idea of manipulating the ground to do as you like; dig, pile, etc. A lot of games that are out lately do not have this simple feature, which is a defining point in the game for a lot of players. Just keep in mind that everything you walk on, in every random world you generate, can be dug down, through and around... and not just by the players.Block physics. Combined with the above. If you've played this game long enough, it comes as second nature... until you try another game. You'd be amazed at how much feels as though it is lacking in games that don't have these fully implemented physics.Atmosphere, atmosphere and atmosphere! From the music at the title, to the wind-swept pine forests on mountaintops. This game oozes atmosphere out of every pixel. The zombie models might not be as varied as some major titles, but when you're getting your face gnawed off after you step through a broken window of a book store, you'd be hard pressed to complain about the variety of the zombie eating your face off that second! The sheer ""Oh SH**!"" moments like those, make this game something you can't easily forget.Mod-ability is a major key to the game as well. With access to the game's files, you can change many of the game's features to fit your play style. For every update they make that you may not like, just go into the right file and change the value back to something you prefer. This makes many negative features of updates people may not agree with, more bearable as you can simply change them back to something more agreeable.Finally, this game has a reason to it. It has a driving purpose for you to play it. It has a reason you NEED to make sure your base is  up to snuff. It has a reason to make sure you have researched the recipes you need. It has a reason to make sure you explore the areas and learn and scavenge what you can - the 7th day hoards.You will die. When you first play the game, you will die on the 7th day. This isn't a threat or a challenge, this is just a fact. You will think you're tough and you can handle anything this game throws at you, until a few dozen ultra-aggressive, insanely fast zombies come to tear down every inch of the structure you though was unbreakable. And then, every 7th day after that, the zombies only get more difficult.This. This one feature is the one reason you will keep playing the game. Other games have some great base building features in them, but eventually, they lack a threat. 7 Days to Die has some great base building in it, but it will be along and far down the road before you can safely say, the zombies are no longer a threat. In the back of your mind, everything you add to your base will be about ""Will this survive?"" which is something many games in this genre only leave to your imagination, but never put to the test to the same degree as this one does.GET THIS GAME. Whether you have never heard of it, or own every single survival game out there, GET THIS ONE. This will be the only zombie/survival/base building game you will ever need to have in your Steam library. I just give the others in my Steam library a quick little pity smile every time I pass my mouse cursor over them to start this game up..."
76561198001151065,Recommended,251570,13564406,"Posted: 24 December, 2014",all,Panda Cheeks,"My first impression was lackluster. I expected another half-hearted pseudo-sandbox with pushover survival mechanics. My expectations were way off mark.1) 7DtD has one of the most comprehensive crafting sysmtes I seen, even in building within the world, with many tools that provide a variety of benefits and a plethora of resources differing by biome that alter the way you manage your survival. The world is fully detructible, being able to dig and mine (with some decent physics) as well as destroying parts of the landscape (or cityscape), thrown in with many gatherable items for survival purposes.2) Survival itself is key and is directly tied into game play. Managing your hunger and thirst will determine not only how long you will live, but more nuanced features, like stamina and wellness. There are many resources available to satisfy both survival mechanics, but you have to manage them well to maximize their effectiveness, and you have to gather them without dying.3) Zombies are no joke. Even during the day time, if you're hammering on zombies with your crossbow, all it takes is for one not-so-noticeable zombie to flank you, and you're dead. Taking hits from zombies can detriment you in several ways, including bleeding, infection, and being temporarily stunned.At its stage in development, this game is already basically a fully-fledged game, and it only continues to get better with bugfixes and additional content. 10/10"
76561198103478128,Recommended,251570,19355905,"Posted: 28 November, 2015",all,almightypmj,"First of all let me state that this game is still in Alpha, not the final release, not in Beta, but Alpha. So understandably, there's still a lot more content that the developers are planning that have not yet been implemented (such as Mods, NPCs, story/plot, more types of animals, character builds/personalization, many HD models, and much more). That also means that if there are bugs, glitches or pereformance issues that you have complaints about, depending on how critical it is the developers will get to it eventually and release sub version patches (alpha 13.1, alpha 13.2, so on and so on).Now that that's out of the way let's move on.As of V12.5 (literally days if not hours before the release of Alpha 13) after you ""create"" you're character/profile you start out in your underwear in the middle of nowhere with nothing but a bottle of water, a can of food, a torch, and ..... I forget what else, but it's not much.You have a certain amount of time in this starting safe zone (like 5 minutes or something) to procure the materials that you need in order to create your starting survival gear/tools before the zombies start to spawn around you. Collect grass to make grass pants, collect cotton to make cloth armor, some grass, some sticks, and some rocks let you make your first stone axe, some grass and sticks make a bow, and with some feathers, sticks, and rocks/metal scraps you can make some arrows. It's not much, but it will at least allow you to defend yourself.You can see a list of what you are able to craft as well as what materials are needed in your menu, and you can learn recipes for other more advanced items by finding recipe books.Currently your crafting qualityand skill is determined by your level, but I think when Alpha 13 is released it's being changed to a ""use it to improve it"" system. For example, the more you use/craft bows the more proficient you become with them and you can create better quality.You can customize a lot of your settings/gameplay options when starting a game, but in a standard game the zombies walk slowly during the day and run during the night, so you'll probably want to take the oppotunity of your first day to make your basics and then find some kind of shelter to hide in for when night comes (a cabin, a cave, or even dig a hole in the groud and cover it back up from the inside). You also want to be careful about creating noise and heat (chopping down a tree, firing a gun, cooking food in a campfire) that will attract the attention of zombies.The random generated maps are currently infinite in size and come with many different areas to explore called biomes (dessert biome, forest biome, snow, swamp, plains, etc.) and are blended together very well now, so there's not any noticable borders between them anymore.I could go on but this getting a bit long winded alredy, so I'll just let you figure the rest out for yourselves. I highly recommend this game, and it has been a blast seeing all the changes and new content as it has developed."
