76561198034396876,Not Recommended,251570,33557551,Posted: 15 July,all,Blue,"Whilst not revolutionary (minecraft with guns, zombie hordes, and some basic block physics), that mix is pretty solid. I nearly gave this a positive review, even. And you can forgive an early access game a fair few flaws. (Also, please note that I played a fair while offline on steam, so... I do have more hours in this than it seems).But the unfortunate issue that's really hurt the playability of this game is how the dev's problem solve.Players are creative, and rather good at solving problems. So, they would slow zombies to a crawl with water, and wait for them to lose the ability to sense them on bloodmoon nights by just staying safe until dawn, and then letting the horde wander off. They would build bases half-way down cliffs; zeds at the bottom couldn't see you or get to you, zeds at the top would fall and splatter. They would use the penalties to mining underwater to fortify structures. They would, in short, win.The dev's, rather than add new content that would complicate these strategies, instead decided to just do things like remove zombie fall damage. To make zombies ALWAYS move full-speed through water.  To remove zombies suffering the same debuffs as players.As such, the game shoehorns you into playing in some very limited ways, and really tries to steer you towards a house/fort, walls, and spike traps. Which would be okay if that wasn't so godawfully boring.Mine forever to keep up your supplies of iron an concrete. Which, staring at low-res stone walls directly in your face is just boring. Place spikes on the ground, because ones on walls won't hurt them (they'll just attack them from outside the damage radius), and watch zombies just stand there and kind of explode bits off, randomly (which gets old fast) whilst you drop ammo into clumps of idiots with a bad tendency to spin wildly in circles.It just gets tedious, and I personally resented being forced to play in the most energy inefficient possible way.I've also yet to experience a breach. A couple got past the outer perimeter on the 28th night, but they quickly died in the bailey. I'd like to be able to automate dealing with zombies much more, because again, they're tedious, not challenging to deal with by... Two to three days in.At the end of the day, it basically boils down to not being a particularly clever game, that has started to punish clever strategies rather than grow in depth."
