76561197960491075,Recommended,251570,30913358,Posted: 2 April,all,amph,"I was truthfully a little sceptical about the asking price for this game, but this game is excellent! I play co-op with my brother on a private server, and we play for hours on end!Pros:* It doesn't feel like Early-access. The game feels largely complete, but there could be improvements* Crafting and gathering is a very fun aspect, and also important to survival* Death isn't just a number, there's a lot to lose from dying, which encourages safer play: something that makes the game more realistic, and more enjoyable* Zombies are a real threat at night-time, and seem to just sneak up on you. There is very little vision (you can obtain forches etc), but I like that this encourages me to stay indoors and safe* Levelling up earns skill points to increase various things* Fun co-operative playCons:* The AI seems a little sloppy* The graphics and animations feel like early 2000's. While better animations and models would be nice, the game is fine as-is* Currently you can't craft everything you see in the game, which is a little frustrating* The game lacks any kind of tutorial, so your first few hours will be largely confusing. This can be offset by just reading a Steam guideI know there appear to be as many cons as there are pros, but the cons are all negligible. Even for the asking price of $25, this game is truly worth it if you're into zombie survival games"
76561198079350603,Not Recommended,251570,33661807,Posted: 19 July,all,[HG] Snowyamur,"Ever playedMinecraft? You know, that one all-building, crafting, zombie survival game? I sure haven’t, but I know what the game is, and the gameplay and mechanics of7 Days to Dieare very similar to Minecraft. Although7 Days to Dieintroduces itself as a more somewhat-realistic game without the pixel-graphics and block textures, it is also possiblyMinecraft’s more disgusting cousin.What is 7 Days to Die?7 Days to Dieis an Early Access singleplayer and multiplayer building, crafting, open-world zombie survival game that takes place in Navezgane County, Arizona. Navezgane means “Killer of Monsters,” and it is a supposedly-quarantined area infested with the undead. You are a survivor that wakes up in some random part of Navezgane’s vast landscape, where you begin at Day 1, and you have 7 Days to gather supplies, weapons, and resources to construct, fortify, and arm a base to the teeth, capable of withstanding a massive horde on the 7th Night.The game can be played alone or online with others through servers. Online gameplay features servers that can include solely PvE, PvE or PvP, or solely PvP, in which the hosts of said servers can configure with the options to make each server unique and different from many others.Overall, it is either a survival game, or Survival of the Fittest, depending on whether you play alone or on a server.Pros (The Positives)Because7 Days to Dieis basically aMinecraft-replica, it has many replicated characteristics. In addition to being an open-world for the players to explore, the game emphasizes the freedom to make choices and decisionssolely on the player’s accord. You can build, craft, use, destroy, and inhabit whatever they want in this game, so long as they have the required resources. The possibilities are endless in 7 Days to Die, and you will almost never leave this game and move on to another one because of its massive variety.Additionally, different zombie types add uniqueness to gameplay. Some zombies are faster, stronger, slower, or weaker than others, and some are incredibly unique to their own design. The 7th Night do-or-die mechanic, hence the title of the game, gives players an incentive to continue playing and exploring the world of Navezgane to survive, still leaving you with many things to do despite you subconsciously believing you are satisfied and finished.Moreover, the crafting and skill-tree system in7 Days to Dieare huge and varied, let alone unique to the game. As you continue to progress in your survival marathon, you will find rarer resources and stronger weapons. You will transition from bashing with a club, to splattering with a shotgun, to decimating with a rocket launcher. Furthermore, the game has a leveling system that allows you to expand your horizons and truly define your character. Will he/she be a gun-wielding mechanic, or clubbing constructor. The choice is yours, and every time you level up, you will receive points to turn your character into what you want he/she to be.Best of all,you are never truly safe in this game.Cons (The Negatives)Because it is in Early Access, this game will have bugs and issues, that’s inevitable. Recently, the developers have updated the game to A16… and it has been quite a let-down for many players, including myself.Aside from it being in EA for about 3 years, which begs the question, “What are the developersreallydoing for their game?” Patch A16 turns this game from already bad to devastatingly catastrophic.Zombie spawns in7 Days to Dieare a joke. They were balanced in Patch A15, but with A16, I would turn my back for one split-second and notice about 5 zombies behind me, ready to pounce. This new spawning system is especially broken for prefab buildings, and for players fortifying a base on a prefab, beware. There is nothing wrong or n00bish about building and fortifying upon prefabs, but with A16, zombies are likely to spawninsideyour base, making your survival-immersion more frustrating and unrealistic.The skill-tree system has been revised, and has taken a heavy beating. No longer is there a freedom to unlock a skill with points whenever you want; some skills are now heavily-dependent on a larger range of skills, making the game more of a grinding simulator, constantly finding ways to level up faster so that you can unlock that game-changing perk or skill. Skills in this game have not entirely been ruined, but are so far frustrating to deal with and unbalanced. While it’s cleaner, it’s not neater.Harvesting resources in7 Days to Dieeats time up like an LMG eats up caliber bullets. Patch A16 has made harvesting wood harder, turning it into a chore instead of a necessity. Back in A15, you would have gathered so much wood by chopping down only 3 trees, now it takes 15 trees to match that. Mining for resources has improved somewhat with more varied resources received per boulder-node destroyed, but stone-farming has now become tedious work. Nothing is exciting about farming for resources, and it has worsened with A16.Zeds are the worst part. Their damage has been significantly buffed for no apparent reason, enabling them to claw away at cement structures as if they were made from papier-mache. Forget never being safe in this game, you willnever survive in this game for longwith this stupid damage boost.What do I think of this game personally?I like it, I played it with a friend of mine and we had fun building a base. Now it just seems like a mind-numbing chore for me. Additionally, because it is in EA, I’m disappointed with the state of this game being 3 years into EA, even for an Indie.Is it worth buying right now?For 25 USD, or 31 Canadian,absolutely not. While the game has lots of potential and has many things you can do, the time you invest in this game will be wasted given that with every patch, you need to restart your saves to avoid compatibility issues, and every patch is slow as a snail, making me think the developers are lazy. Not only that, but the gamedoesfeel unfinished, with broken graphics and physics everywhere.Overall, why do you not recommend7 Days to Die?7 Days to Dieis the very definition of a time-sink. You will spend countless hours playing and progressing, all to be for nothing because one patch demands a fresh restart to avoid compatibility issues. I like to prevent compatibility issues on my own mods forStellaris, and I definitely love not restarting the progress I already made.Again, it has been 3 years in Early Access for this game. What the f**k is going on with the work being made on this game?"
