,Not Recommended,251570,32099251,Posted: 31 May,all,Lactose the Intolerant,"This game is amazing, despite the fact its a bit hard to recommend to many.Lets start with the positives. The gameworld itself is amazing. Nearly anything you see in the game can be interacted with on some level. You can destroy or upgrade literally everything you see. Very good interactivity. The combat is excellent- its so damn visceral. It actually sounds like it hurts when you hit something. The sound is amazing- every action feels like it has weight to it, from mining materials to looting. The sounds are all super satisfying no matter what you do in-game. The worlds come in two flavors, a hand-built world called Navesgane or a randomly generated world with extremely complex and impressive algorithims. Finally, there's the 7 Day hordes. These hordes are the high-lights of the game, in which zombies will rush you every 7 days. They are constantly running at night, and can see you through walls. Your only option is to build a sturdy base and play defensively, which I love. The game is also super brutal, which really adds tension and weight to how you play. Be careful while you play, because there's a lot on the line.There really is so much to like about this game that I haven't even listed here. Its just special as a game- a mix between DayZ, Left 4 Dead, and Minecraft. But there are a LOT of things about this game that I simply can't recommend to many but the most dedicated. For one, its brutally unforgiving, like I mentioned, which means a massive learning curve. Sometimes the game is just downright unfair. I had to tweak the game settings for my first one or two hundred hours before I could learn to play on default settings. Every time you die you lose overall health (called wellness in this game) AND you can possibly lose all of your stuff in your backpack, depending on the server. The game is real tough, no ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥tting here. If you want to learn how to do something besides what the bare-bones tutorials teach you, you better bone up on the 7 Days to Die wiki and watch some videos on good base-building. The game is also kind of ugly. Make no mistake, if you have a good computer you can really see some of the most gorgeous sights in gaming- but it looks chunky and slightly pixelated. Then there are the bugs- this game has been in ♥♥♥♥ing alpha since its release in 2013. No clue when the Fun Pimps are gonna finish this, but expect to play the game on cheat mode due to the frustrating amount of ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t that the glitches will subject you to (since you will likely lose your hard-earned items will need the creative menu to get them back). Also expect constant wipes of your game, since each new update requires it. Finally, one of the biggest things about this game that makes me hate it, is how easy it is for your hard work to get completely wiped out. The zombies, I understand. But having to lose everything in your storage devices because something underneath it collapses is ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t, and its way too easy to get griefed in this game.This game is without a doubt extremely fun with more than one player (and if you lack friends like I do, it is still fun but only to a certain point before you run out of things to do), but I have to say that this game is very hard to recommend to most people that just want a game they can pick up and play. Its very frustrating, very difficult, very very time consuming, and it is way, way too easy to lose your progress. I only recommend to those who are truly dedicated to a unique and brutal experience.I can't give a proper 1-10 rating on this, since it really depends on the person. But if you're the right kind of person, this game will go miles with you, like it has with me."
