,Recommended,251570,33701553,Posted: 21 July,all,Starrweaver,"I'm not the sort to play a first person survival game, and yet here I am. I'm also not a fan of zombies, ever since my kids talked me into playing Left 4 Dead. Nope. I kept hearing smokers and witches when I wasn't even playing the game! But I joined together with my son and daughter on a multiplayer game. It was a first time for my daughter and I.  We were getting a crash course in survival in-game from my son.My first load up felt a bit like a realistic Minecraft, quests to get small stones, wood and make a stone ax. Okay I've been in this before. I've played Minecraft years ago with my kids when it came out. I even tried out Creativerse a while ago, so I felt some familiar parallels in this one.Took me forever to figure out how to get fiber, punching grass was a helpful accident which resulted in me playing lawnmower with my hands. lol I also discovered some of those thicker bushes gave me wood. That was a helpful bit I could've used sooner. Taking down a small tree by punching it took a while and I'm fairly sure it hurt my hands. At least in my mind, that would make sense. But then, this is a game.For some odd reason, my daughter who is the bane of all zombies she's encountered, was more disturbed by these stumbling and shambling maggot condos than usual. Not sure why, but the whole atmosphere was very tense. It was like waiting to hear the footsteps behind you, you swore you heard just a second ago. Even she didn't really understand why these zombies disturbed her so.So if you are a zombie nut, these may just be a new group to check out. There's a fair variety of creepy crawlies to get aquainted with. The idea is to find a place to fortify and survive the Horde night which happens every 7 days. I know I should have been helping on the first Horde night, but I was only level 3, what could I do? The roof felt a lot safer than being below with those decaying carcasses bashing in through the fortifications and extra doors.I will admit that I did enjoy scavenging the area, collecting up things to use and even exploring a few buildings. It took me some time, but I even learned to aim my bow so my arrows actually hit something. This game has some real physics action so the arrows at a distance arc... so aiming a bit above my target actually took of a head or two. Yeah headshot! I do a bit better at headshots when the targets are closer. Though I've a bad habit with taking groin shots, especially when the zombie's down. I'll shoot for between the legs if I'm not close enough to target the head. I figure why not? It should work, right?Anyway, I did find that playing on solo with the intension of finding and killing stuff did help with improving my skill with a bow and digging was a great way to get up athletics and such. I also found it to get easier to deal with pop up zombies and such after stumbling on them since I wasn't paying attention where I should have. So now that the new update has rolled in, it's time to start up a new game together.I'm more prepared, feel more sure of my abilities and know how to watch for dangerous situations better. I think I'll be together with my kids, helping to defend our shelter next time the Horde comes to visit. I'm really glad I gave this game a try and even though I love zombies even less than before, but I feel like I'm ready to take a few more down this time."
76561198063120601,Recommended,251570,18747538,"Posted: 29 October, 2015",all,Squirting Elephant,"This one along with Ark Survival are the best survival games out there right now (at the time of writing). The game is in a very playable state and has a great crafting system and the building part is the best part of this game. You can make crazy creations above and underground, it won't affect performance like in other games (Space Engineers...).But sadly drains a LOT of performance in multiplayer due to bad optimization. Therefor finding a decent server is hard. Bad servers are plagued by hackers, cheating admins or simply have no zombies at all or when they spawn they don't move because the server has no CPU left for that... Basically world-objects like supply drops, enemies, physics, etc. no longer update on poor servers with more players than they can handle.But luckily there are some good servers out there. You just gotta find 'em.The game has sadly a lot of nasty bugs that can eventually become pretty annoying. But for a casual gamer this game is just awesome. And there is in my opinion no better zombie survival game out there right now. Singleplayer is very stable, multiplayer is not.The game supports both online PVE and PVP."
