,Recommended,251570,11882090,"Posted: 27 August, 2014",all,Mons,"Probably one of the best alpha games I've played. It features a lot of stuff you could see in Minecraft, but adds more realism to it. In turn, 7DTD lacks some advanced minecraft mechanics such as functioning vehicles (boats / minecarts / red stone powered torches or mechanics etc.) The game is more focused on survival, and the zombies really are a force to be reckoned with. They never stop. You could build a fort, and assuming you don't exploit bugs / glitches, the zombies will eventually get through with a horde(s) big enough to destroy multiple walls before you can repair them.  Some of the gravity mechanics seem to be broken, where certain building tiles will fall apart for seemingly no reason. This is especially true when building a fort above an underground mining complex, as the game will somehow link the empty ground 50 blocks down to the fort above ground; making supports futile. A good variety of weapons, though rarity is a thing. Once you create molds for items you can start smelting your own brass bullet casings, or iron ingots for pickaxes and other tools. There comes a point when you don't need to scavenge anymore and you can become self-sufficient.The biggest thing I wanted in Minecraft was its survival element; but it was really boring as enemies (aside from endermen/creepers) did little to interact with the world. In 7DTD you see zombies attack stags, pigs, rabbits, they tear down walls and even at times terrain. At night they run, but you can turn this feature off. Some of the AI bugs have been fixed, though you'll see one or two everynow and again where they get stuck on certain things.One of the best things about 7DTD is its customisable options. It rarely ever forces you to play the game the developers set. You can have shorter days, longer days, more frequent air drops, more or less zombies, higher or lower damage received/given, loot rarity, loot respawn, etc. You don't have to restart another game to change them, you can go back to main menu, tweak some settings, and hop back in to see the effects.Random world generation is perhaps the biggest and best addition to this game. The only problem is that it lacks major cities and towns (too rare and far in between).The game supports Co-Op or PvP, up to 8 players I think, though you can go higher but chances of server crashing increases. Definitely recommend this game; it's one of the few that didn't just hop on the zombie survival hype train and abandon it as soon as things start to go south. It also delivers on its promises and doesn't promise to make something that will take them 3~4 years down the road to implement.Oh and with Co-Op, I've found it to be easiest by using Hamachi. That worked like a charm with no hassles."
