76561198051192704,Recommended,251570,15742029,"Posted: 8 May, 2015",all,raiders5000,"Based on 86 hoursPatch Alpha 11.4I have to update my review. The last one was based on 30 hours of gameplay. That might've been when the game was at Alpha 5, 6 or 7.This is for you, the reader & gamer; NOT the devs!You are probably looking to invest time in a survival game. There are plenty out there, including ""Survival: Postapocalypse Now"" selling for $4.99 at the time of this post. It doesn't matter cause you will NOT find a better, more complete survival gameplay experience, IN ALPHA for that matter, anywhere out there today.- 7DTD now uses the Unity 5 game engine. Depending on your system, the graphics are fabulous. Even when running at any setting less than HIGH or ULTRA. Excellent framerate and control responsiveness.- The gameplay has really been expanded. The zombies behave like zombies but they aren't totally out of control or spamming wrecklessly all over the game ruining your experiences. That doesn't mean they aren't tough, though. They can be hell to deal with at times. Very challenging encounters will be had.- The crafting system is much better than most. Items are abundant in 7DTD, BUT, the crafting system is where this game is shining. You will have access to a host of recipes from the offset; however, you will gain more recipes from exploring the huge map (more on that later). You can craft weapons, armor, food, health kits, supplies, housing materials, tools, resources, resoucres for other resources, booby traps, mines, smithing items...the works.- Your character can level up based on a lot of things like: killing, cooking & eating, or just surviving over a period of time; meaning the day and night cycles. I still haven't quite figured that part out yet but i'm sure you'll find it in the Wikis.- THE MAP! Oh god, the map. This map is huge. The devs have done an excellent job of making a world in which it will literally take FOREVER to explore everything. You will come across stuff to explore almost at every third step. There is trash on the sides of the road, in the road, on the road, in the woods, in the desert, in the snow, in the buildings, on the hills, by the river bed...there is a chance to loot and find USEFUL stuff all the time. There are cars to loot, buildings to loot, graveyards to loot, zombies to loot, chest to loot, backpacks to loot, purses to loot, suitcases to loot, gunsafes to loot, camping grounds to loot, dead half eaten bodies to loot, ruins to loot, dead animals to loot....- At the time of the review, we can only hunt deer, rabbits and pigs. They make for good eating and supplies. They help boost your character level as well. The only downside is that I can't craft a head mount for my walls. I would luv to be able to kill a deer, loot its head, and craft a trophy mount for my wall. There was a post somewhere that said the game will add bears. I hope they add moose, wolves, bobcats, badgers and mountain lions too. And add that freakin' wall mount to the crafting system.*** But lets talk about what you came here for: the gameplay. When Unity 5 was introduced, I died a lot. They made the game more difficlt at the beginning by making early craftable tools weaker. By dying so much, I had to change my tactics. Now that I'm used to it, I find the gameplay much better this way. It forces me to explore the environment in search of better loot, weapons and resources to craft.Speaking of dying, as bad as it is to have to start over, the good thing is the random starting position you're subjected to if you have NOT made a home base. Without my bed roll, I could die in one place and respawn a world away in another place. Oh, don't worry. Everything I had in my backpack and on my belt is still in the place I died. I just have to get there. Sometimes that would take 7 days and nights, I kid you not.So I have a choice: pick up loot and start another backpack or not touch anything and try to get back to MY backpack. Or I can place a waypoint on the backpack and start a new backpack. So if I die again, I'll know where both backpacks are. But that's neither here nor there because what I want to share with you is what happened when I respawned.+ One time I respawned in a rural area on the side of the road. I made a trek toward my last backpack and ran across this HUGE factory. I never saw it before and didn't know it was in the game. Of course, I had no weapons, no armor nor clothes of any kind, and a crap load of zombies alerted to my presence. I'll be back!+ I respawned in a field of tall grass. After running for my life, I came across this large campsite. While still running from zombies during the twilight of the day-to-evening cycle, I blow up. As I'm waiting to respawn, I'm asking myself, ""What the hell just happened?""++ On the very next respawn, I went back to the place I blew up. By now it is completely dark and the zombies are in their night time frenzy. I get close to my back pack and ""KABOOM"", I blow up again. Okay, now I'm ♥♥♥♥♥♥!+++ New respawn during the evening. Crouched down, didn't move, and waited for daylight. Made my way back to the land of death...and my two backpacks. Well holy ♥♥♥♥! Found out why I died twice without a zombie touching me. This ain't no ""campsite""! It's a military bivouacing installation heavily protected by a huge mine field. Again, something I had NO IDEA was here! So now zombies are chasing me. Fine. I maneuver in such a way that they perish to beautifully orchestrated explosions across the early morning skyline. Now, lets get down to business! :)As I sign off here, I'm on my way to retrieve another backpack that has all my armor and other goodness I need to correlate with the goodness I just looted. No spoilers!!!In short, I not only recommend 7DTD; I encourage you to try it for yourself. I thought about getting The Forest & Project Zomboid among other titles. To be honest, nothing holds a candle to 7DTD. There are so many things to do that never get accomplished by the time the next patch is rolled out. It took me a realtime week to loot out a town of about 16 different buildings. I looted several houses, a few garages, a gas station, store, a school and a couple of municipal buildings. The next week, I strolled down the street and found an even bigger neighborhood. If you really want something to invest in, to cure that bordem, to find an ultimate survival gaming experience; I say place your bets on this thoroughbred. Your own experiences will be better than ANYTHING you find on videos OR reviews!"
