,Recommended,251570,29287479,Posted: 15 January,all,Gamboh,"7 Days to Die is a content-heavy, co-op focused, zombie survival game.For those who like to build and craft in their zombie games, and who also have at least one dedicated friend to play it with, this game is a must-have.The default world map is quite large, featuring a number of different biomes and a wealth of opportunities for scavenging. Exploring the world itself is an exciting and dynamic experience. Smashing through the walls of a house in order to raid it for goods is always very satisfying.Every block can be destroyed. All blocks are subject to gravity and without support will collapse into heaps of trash. This is a GREAT feature and works very well. Zombies can damage and destroy structures, slowly digging holes through your base.You can dig hundreds of feet down into the ground, minecraft-style. Every bit of terrain in the entire game is a fully-realized, voxel-based solid mass that can be destroyed or otherwise harvested. It is very impressive, and only paralleled by minecraft itself, a game with much less fidelity.Constructing massive castles out of steel and concrete and surrounding them with huge, menacing death-moats is always a lot of fun. All the better if your walls and structures are bristling with deadly spikes!Hiding from zombies works quite well, depending on zombie difficulty settings. If you don't like to stay tied down, you can totally live the life of a roaming scavenger.The Long Game here generally ends up being to construct your own fort knox; a place to store your riches and craft goods into bullets, with which to slaughter zombies. It is a LOT of fun to be powerful in 7 Days to Die, and a real challenge to get there.I enjoyed my time with this game, but there are a couple of things that prevent me from coming back. I'll list some of those here:-Instead of defending your home on blood-moon nights, or during other large raids, you can just leave the place and huddle in a shack somewhere for safety. Zombies are attracted by noise, constructions, and lights. Zombies also only spawn near players. So if there are no players near noisy, attractive features, there will be few zombies.-There is an XP and leveling system that encourages you to engage in repeated, menial tasks so you can be more successful at important things. The end result being that my friends and I often spent a lot of time crafting hundreds of useless items and throwing them into a pit, just to level our skills. The skill XP system encompasses everything you do in the game. This includes: Smashing down objects like doors and walls, mining, digging, shooting, running, healing, crafting quality, and the amount of damage you deal with each and every individual type of weapon in the game, seperately.-The aforementioned XP system is tied to a specific character, in a specific map save. If you try to bring this character to a new map, or to a friend's game or server, their stats will be ZERO anywhere other than where they were created. Considering how long it takes to level up, and how pitifully impotent a level 1 character is, this is a major problem.-You will spend the first major portion of the game grinding up your Archery skill, and then find very quickly that when you run out of arrows, you are completely helpless. Melee requires a huge amount of grinding in order to be effective (and is EXTREMELY dangerous to attempt.) Firearms are rare early on, and not a viable option until well into a playthrough. It's generally going to take you more than ten hours to get together what you need to START crafting bullets. As a result, a practical player will inevitably fall into shooting thousands of arrows at zombies. This makes my next point especially important:-Archery feels like♥♥♥♥♥♥ Considering just how much if it you have to do, one would expect shooting zombies with arrows to be fun and engaging. It is not. The animations are stiff, the bow is ugly, and the arrows completely disappear in flight, making it extremely difficult to judge distance and trajectory. Zombies do not have a visual response when hit by arrows, and it takes MANY arrows to dispatch even basic enemies. I personally had such a hard time figuring out whether I was even hitting more distant enemies, that I entirely gave up on archery, and struggled for hours to grind up my melee abilities to a usable level.tip: Rust and Skyrim are a couple of examples of good archery in games.-There are a few items that sort of 'gatekeep' the late-game crafting. Before you can make bullets, guns, and some other mechical objects, you'll need to find tools. These tools are very rare, and force you to go out and scour the countryside. Those who prefer to stay at home and play the stationary survival game (such as myself) will inevitably end up struggling with this. The drop chance for the tools is VERY low. My buddy and I looked for these tools for an embarassingly long time. We checked the wiki, read the discussion board, talked to a few people and generally gamed-it to maximize our chances of finding the tools. It still took us a FEW whole days of IRL playing this damn game to find the stupid things. Upon finally recieving them, I was so angry that I didn't even want to play  anymore. Recent patches have made the tools more common than previously, but they are still too rare for my taste."
