76561197970726026,Recommended,251570,16090814,"Posted: 30 May, 2015",all,Gumbercules007,Really cool game.Been Playing it since Alpha 5.Every update the Devs do just makes it better and better.Well worth the moneyHighly Highly recommend this game
,Recommended,251570,16938703,"Posted: 8 July, 2015",all,Stormtroop97,"You can build a super fortress and live like a king, or you can accidentally cut a tree down wrong and die. You can kill more zombies than Rick Grimes or you can eat broken glass and die from internal bleeding. 7 Days to Die is about choice, and it is choice that sets this game apart from other survival games.Essentially this game is a zombie survival game, but rather than be like Day Z or other games of similar enviornments 7 Days to Die has a large focus on both exploration and building. The greatest thing about it, is that it forces you to participate in both aspects if you want to survive. The game is brutal. Don't be surprised if your first night i the game is spent warding off 50+ zombies from your tiny refuge inside a local house. And as the game progresses don't be surprised when you're warding off more than that from your fortress built from the ground up by you. Did I mention that this is just the default normal difficulty? The game's difficulty brilliantly forces you to explore the world around you for necessary supplies, while also forcing you to build a safe haven because you won't find one anywhere prebuilt. So now that you hopefully have a basic understanding of the game, let's get a little more in depth.ExplorationExploration in 7 Days to Die is not going to be a big surprise to you if you've played any other survival game ever. You walk around a world and look inside any possible thing in hopes to find something of value. While it may not always make sense (oh sure, killing a zombie dog in real life always gets me two cans of gas), it is certainly rewarding to open up another bag of trash and find that last pistol part you needed to complete your weapon. There is nothing particularly original about the exploration, but it keeps it rewarding and entertaining so there really isn't much to complain about. I will however say that exploration is key to the game, as most supplies you will need to find to stay alive, especially in the beginning. In fact most items you can't even craft without finding schematics that teach you recipes for things such as ammo and armor. So there is always a reason to get back out there and explore, which does go aways to keep you interested in affairs outside your own stronghold.Building/CraftingThis is where I believe 7 Days to Die really shines. Where as most survival games are about finding supplies and minimal building, 7 Days to Die is about finding supplies andA LOTof building. You are offered a wide range of building blocks and all around construction tools to really create and personalize your own base in ways not many games have. I hate to make this comparrison, but the building is most comparable to minecraft albeit with many more things to create. On top of buildings, you can also craft your own weapons, tools, armor, and accessories such as chairs and tables for your house. Very few games have a fleshed out building system like 7 Days to Die, and to miss out on it would just be a shame.The WorldWhen starting up a new world you have the option of one of two things. You can choose their prebuilt game world ""Navezgane"" or you can choose a randomly generated world. While both are similar in the fact that they have buildings, heaps of supplies, and all different biomes on them, Navezgane is generally a little more organized simply because of the fact that it was hand crafted by the devs rather than randomly produced by a computer. Either way both world types are a joy to be in and produce a fresh experience with every play through. Several biomes are available in the game including forests, tundras, deserts, and burned forests. Buildings are also spawned frequently throughout the world, with each biome having its own set of building types. Admittedly though it would be nice to see a broader range of building types. Many of the houses are essentially copy/paste with small adjustments in a poor attempt to hide the lack of variety. Overall the world is interesting enough, but I'd like to see a greater variety between housing types to keep the game from getting stale.Graphics/OptimizationThis is probably the game's weakest point. The game looks ok, but far from breathtaking. To give the devs some credit they have improved the graphics dratically from previous builds I've seen online, but some work is needed. Speaking of work needed, optimization is an issue for this game. I'm on a pretty up to date PC that can run games like Battlefield 4 on ultra settings like a charm, yet I still get frequent frame dips when running the game on the lower middle settings. Once again this has improved through updates, and the game is definitely playable it would just be welcomed if the game could run a bit smoother. However there are many bugs that plague this game. While I haven't found any game breaking ones, you will have frequent issues of general things getting wonky on you. The game is of course in early access however, so this should be expected.CombatThere really isn't too much to write about the combat in 7 Days to Die. You find or craft weapons to use against massive hordes of zombies. These weapons (as well as tools) must be maintained using varoius repair items to keep a weapons damage up. The melee weapons can be a little hard to usae at time given they require you to come close to a zombie to use them, but guns feel powerful and are fun to use albeit smalll glitches sometimes pull you out of the immersion. You also have a range of explosives such as TNT and mines to use againt your undead foe. Overall the combat is a rewarding experience that may require a little work but gets the job done in a satisfactory manner.Community/DevsThe community is fantastic! Any issue I've had was openly welcomed by the community, and the willingness to help out was a welcome breath of fresh air from other games with a toxic community. And the devs on this game at The Fun Pimps are some of the most interactive and helpful I've ever seen. They release frequent patches and updates about progress, ensuring that this game won't be abandoned half way through like so many other early release titles. I have no doubt that this game will continue to grow under their development.OverallOverall this game is a unique and brilliant experience. Whether you love the slow and careful nature of building for a few hours or the fast paced rushing nature of killing undead freakbags I have no doubt you will find yourself having a lot of fun with 7 Days to Die. I've had the game for less than a week and have 38 hours on it. So just make sure you're ready to abandon your friends and family when you purchase this game!"
