76561197980523260,Recommended,251570,22768782,"Posted: 2 May, 2016",all,Stone_Templar,"It was day 7 and I knew I wasn't going to be ready. Too little ammo found in time, too few hours spent prepping the walls. Worst of all, I didn't have enough light, not by a long shot. Those last few flicks of sun glimmering gold through the trees made my stomach lurch. Behind me, where the shadows of night grew, there was screaming in the distance. The dogs reached me first, packs of baying hounds, savagely driving across the field laden with spikes. Some went down, yet others ran even with prongs of wood embedded in them, uncaring, mindless zombies. I unloaded rifle rounds with unsteady shots, I couldn't help but shake, the sound of wailing grew ever stronger and before even a few dogs were down the rest of the undead were swarming the front wall. Flesh clambering over flesh, driving some down into the spikes only to climb over thier own dead and ascend. Spider zombies scaling the walls from behind, forcing me to turn my back to them and fire the last of my ammo. There was nothing left to do but desperate measures. I had found her in the trunk of a car, pure steel, heavy as sin. I named her Vera after my lost ones. Zombies were soft, and the sledge was hard as it arced down onto the first. Bones crunched, it collapsed, step back, swing again. More screaming. This time it was me. They were going down, but so was I. No choice. I lied about the ammo thing. I left one. In the pistol. Under this entire thing I had placed every last barrel of gas I had found. And that last bullet well... it sank into the metal with a flash and as I watched pieces of zombie all around me and my fort shatter I was sure I was done for, ears battered and ringing from the explosion. When I opened my eyes in a fine haze of falling red mist, I could see the blast was just right. Just far enough away to spare me, shivering, bruised, covered in gore, atop the shattered smouldering ruins of my fort. It was time to eat some soup and splint my arm, in a few hours the sun would rise, and I would need to prepare much. Day 7 it seems, was just the beginning.This game keeps getting better and better."
