76561198095495868,Recommended,251570,25882759,"Posted: 6 October, 2016",all,Last Tardis,"I bought this game somewhere around Alpha 12, and it has gone from strength to strength ever since. It has everything a zombie survival game should have and a whole lot more to boot, which includes :-•	A great variety of weapons and armour to suit a number of play styles.•	The ability to construct any base your imagination can conceive, above or below ground.•	A levelling up system that allows you to specialise in certain weapon or armour types.•	The ability to improve your crafting, construction and mining skills.•	The flexibility to hunt for food or grow your own.•	A large predetermined map with the option to play a randomly generated one.•	The impetus to prepare for the inevitable horde every 7 days, lest you be caught off guard.I could go on, however the point is this game is fantastic, adaptive and a must for anybody who is a fan of the genre.People often complain about how slow updates are being released, about how a console version was released before it was finished in order to make money etc. Guess what? That is how small development teams, like The Fun Pimps, have to operate in order to survive and to continue game development and production. The game can be buggy in places and glitchy in others, but so what, it is in Alpha after all and they rely on player feedback to help them iron out the creases. I have 273.9 hours of play time at the time of writing this review and I will add many more to that total as time goes on. I can't recommend this game enough, just bare with the progress and I know we'll all be rewarded in the end.Update-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------Having watched the weekly Q&A YouTube sessions and Alpha 16 updates from one of The Fun Pimps development team, Mad Mole, it is clear to see that the game will definitely have the experience enhanced. Additions in future Alpha's include electricity, enhanced base defence options, different modes of transport and alternative ways to gather food; this is only a small selection of the additions to the game so I would recommend going to YouTube and seeing for yourself."
,Recommended,251570,26056244,"Posted: 15 October, 2016",all,davosaurus.rex,"Not only is this game currently fun and playable, but with every iteration, the devs seem to always implement the exact things that you want them to. Now in alpha 15, the game seems to really have acquired a level of polish that makes it seem more like a beta than an alpha, but it remains in alpha because the devs keep coming up with new and interesting ways to improve the four itches this game scratches:Survival: explore, salvage points of interest, eat, drink, harvest mats, and craft (clothing, weapons, and gear) to help you survive the zombie apocalypse.Roleplay: Customize the look of your survivor and then find/craft gear to customize yourself further. Earn experience through numerous activities (not just killing zeds), and use level points to select perks or increase your current capabilities. Skills also increase as you use them.Base Building/Tower defense: 7 Days isn't a tower defense game per se, but as you build a defensible base, you will actively be thinking about fire lanes, choke points, traps, and fall back zones. Plus, there are a variety of materials to build with, so you can make your base look nice too.Multiplayer: Zombies tend to show up in hordes, so you should bring some friends. You really should. Plus, due to the level up system, survivors can spec themselves out into a certain niche. Maybe someone becomes the close weapons expert, another is good with crafting, while another is fantastic at finding the best loot (or buying the best equipment for cheaper when you find a wasteland trader). Hordes take into account your group, though, so don't expect safety in numbers. Watch each others' backs!Caveats: the game still possesses its share of glitches. Each iteration brings new glitches, but bugs are generally stomped out in short order. After a few months of patches, after a new alpha release, the game becomes quite stable. Alpha 15 is surprisingly free of glitches, but there are still a few issues you might run into. The only issues I've seen so far revolve around the mini bike. A friend drove one onto a spike at the local trader. He can't drive the bike off the spike, and he can't destroy the spike, since it's part of the protected base. I know my friend shouldn't have done that, but he can be a bit of a nipple head. Also, if you jump off your bike while it's moving, it might become borked. I know that seems like more of a feature than a glitch, but reloading the game allows you to access it again, so it seems more like an issue to me. The issue always seem to be little things like these- nothing to completely derail the fun, so I still recommend it.At it's current price, and my current time played, this game has an extreme amount of value- about three cents per hour, in my case. It's definitely worth a buy if you're into the styles of gameplay mentioned, in a post zombie apocalyptic wrapper.TLDR: If reading is challenging, then watch the trailer instead...sheesh!"
