,Recommended,251570,10833668,"Posted: 26 June, 2014",all,castorquinn,"In Brief7 Days to Dieis Day Z-style zombie survival strongest in collaborative play.Most valuable resource:Moments of genuine fear for your life.Of interest to:people who want their zombie apocalypse to be gritty rather than comic-book, or who want to work with their friends to survive.I wrote a review for this game way back when I got it, when I had six hours in it, back in Alpha 5.  Now in Alpha 9 the game has developed and improved so much that I routinely point at it whenever people lambast Early Access as a concept.  7 Days is the very best example I know of an Early Access game on steam that was already a good, playable experience and which has, with community involvement, only become better with each update.I don't want to start listing off features as the game is adding new and improving existing features all the time - just like zombies, I want this review to remain timeless.  What I will say is that since the inclusion of infinite randomly-generated maps, the game has really opened up.  My friend an I originally holed up in the city at which we spawned, hiding on the top floor of an apartment building, scavenging food from the fridges and cupboards of the departed, eking out a meagre existence, until finally, terrorised too many times by acid-vomiting cops, ferocious dogs and the patient stalking of giant wasps, we just picked a direction and walked out into the wilderness.  We walked for hours, raiding every house we passed, watching our food and water supplies slowly diminishing, until finally, out of food, miles from our city base, in a great canyon in an open plain, we made crossbows and started hunting deer.  It took time, and we developed skills needed to take down the beasts.  We fought off zombies attracted by the smell of fresh meat, tracked down every air drop, came up with a plan to gather essential resources and cook food on the go, and then, after days of playing the game together, we felt like we had a handle on things.  With new armour, improved combat skills and a sense of confidence we returned to the city ... and spent a solid hour screaming other over vent as we struggled to survive.Zombie survival is a flooded genre.  What makes this game stand out are that the developers are constantly balancing those elements that focus on survival.  Food drops with just slightly less than the frequency you need it to, but the fullness of your belly is linked to your stamina and health.  Your health regens, but slowly, making you run away from fights that go south and cower for in-game hours waiting until you have recovered.  The crossbow is an exceptional weapon, but requires you to constantly gather feathers for bolts, compelling you to scavenge and keep moving to keep your ammunition count up.  Killing every zombie you see uses time, weapon durability and ammunition, and risks injury, but it also reduces the zombie spawn rate in an area, forcing to decide whether to kill or to avoid.  Zombies will always attack your base, so you make it strong enough to survive the night and then spend the morning repairing the damage.  Guns are powerful weapons, but also make noise, attracting other zombies.  Like no other zombie survival game 7 Days actually feels like survival.Special reference needs to be made to the variety of zombies.  Each looks, moves, sounds and fights a little differently, but the design is perfectly cohesive.  You don't feel you are fighting a cavalcade of comic book nasties; there is a consistency to the way the different zombies operate.  Terrain makes crawlers hard to shoot, but they can injure your legs, making it harder to run away, so you don't want to close with them.  Bloated corpses are really tough to take down, but go down quickly to a head shot, compelling you to stop and aim mid-fight to remove them before they reach you.  Burned corpses have a weird shambling gait that means their head is constantly ducking and bobbing, messing up your shots at range.  The charge of a dog is terrifying, but if you can hold your cool a clean head shot will end them before they reach you.  Wasps - and this is really clever - you can hear coming, their buzzing taunting you, but they don't attack immediately, and in fact targetting them with a weapon causes them to back off, making fighting them - especially when there are other targets to focus on - a real game of stoplight.  Nurses are always worth killing as they sometimes carry essential medications.  Big men may drop sham sandwiches which might keep you fed if you are starving but at the risk of reducing your stamina, preventing you from running from enemies.There are still some balance issues with the game - weapon damage is not in line with materials cost to make them, certain very cheap building materials have very high damage resistance, hordes on the new infinite map are far too scarce.  There are some bugs and some missing features - most notably for me the server time advances when you are not playing, meaning hard work and progress and using up resources from one session don't carry through to the next.  But these are all being tweaked as the game develops, and they are minor things.  If they change nothing else about this game it is already well worth the price, and is a complete experience.As one final word I encourage you to play this game with friends.  Get a private server, set up a skype call, and work together.  It only enhances the survival apocalypse feel of the game."
