,Recommended,251570,26111206,"Posted: 18 October, 2016",all,Kyoujin Anei,"With the newest A15 update, which has updated the game even further and brought much more substance to the game, I figured it was a good time to do a review.Originally, I hated this game back when I first bought it, back around the time the original game came out. It has become a complete turnaround for me, and currently it's a game I'm very addicted to.Before I go on, I do want to say that the majority of my experience in this game is in single player. But I'm sure multiplayer with randoms can be just as exciting as a game like DayZ. And playing the game with just friends, well.. it can become an incredible co-op experience.First off, I love survival-type games like DayZ and the like (more specifically, DayZ Epoch/Overpoch and DayZ Origins). I also love base building, hording weapons/items/etc, and stuff like that. In this game, building a base, as well as going out and getting supplies, building up my arsenal and so on, is a lot of fun.Build a base, build defenses, take care of your survival needs such as hunger and hydration (which goes even deeper with having to be careful about your temperature, and diseases), and survive the hordes that come every seven days - hence the name of the game. To make everything all the more better, the game includes RPG elements that reward you for killing zombies, scavenging, building and much more. It all becomes together as an incredibly addictiveIf you're new and you want to get settled in before getting overwhelmed, there are plenty of options in single player that allows you to change the difficulty. You can even turn off zombies, which can allow you to build a base in peace, before you decide to take on the hordes. There are a lot of options, from changing how much loot there is out in the world, to how thick the zombie population is in the world.. from difficulties varying from ""Very Easy"" to ""Very Hard.""As you work on your base, you can go out and loot, level up, kill zombies and try to find weapons, equipment and building supplies to make your life a lot easier. The RPG system makes the game all the more addicting, as I stated before.There are a lot of options now when it comes to building bases, whether you're using different materials (wood, scrap metal, concrete, etc). Making an ultimate base that can stand a beating will takes time to build, as you'll generally want to use concrete, which will take awhile to craft. It's a good end-game type scenario to go for, and while you wait, you can make bases made out of wood to start you out. It doesn't take that long to build a simple base with wood, and with the right supplies, you can even upgrade your wooden base to more solid materials, such as scrap metal, brick, concrete and more. Meaning, you don't have to destroy your starter base made out of wood. Instead, you can upgrade it/build around it. And with the A15 update, there are a ton of different things you can build for your base, to make it your own original fortress. Just look up images of what people have done with their bases in the game, especially bases built in the current A15 build.Create a simple log cabin in the woods and live out your days in the wild. Dig yourself a secret underground bunker, with a giant maze of underground mining tunnels. Find a mountain and dig in, build a fortress that zombies and bandits alike would have trouble getting into, using both your structures and the mountain to protect you and your loot. Or make it easy, find an existing building in the world and customize it to your liking (just be aware of zombies spawning nearby).Heck, you can actually build a castle with a moat and a working drawbridge - though I'd recommend filling the moat with spikes and other defenses, as zombies aren't really bothered by water!Even if you aren't into base building, there's still a lot to do. Killing zombies, collecting items.. and if you're playing multiplayer, and if you're into that sort of thing, you can hunt players if you prefer a more PvP element. I don't have much experience with that in this game so I can't really go into it, but with my experience, I can't imagine it being bad.There's so much to collect and build on, and the game is still in early access.. meaning, there'll be even more added. And there's already a lot of different items to collect in the world as is, so it's extremely exciting to think about how the game will turn out once it's officially out of early access!In the end, the base building and looting mixed with the RPG element makes it a game that's not only incredibly addictive, it also gives it endless replayability. Your skills in the RPG department can effect many things. It can effect the level of loot you find, with the more you level up, the better level of loot you'll find. You can level up your Rifle skills, Handgun, Blunt or Bladed Weapons, and more. Focus on leveling on one in particular, or try to raise all your skills at the same time.Each time you level up - or complete missions - you are rewarded skill points. You can level up your skills by using these skill points, and/or you can also level up certain abilities by other means. Such as, if you want to raise your Scavenging skill, you can spend points in it. Otherwise, each time you loot an object, you gain experience towards your Scavenging skill. Same goes for pretty much all the rest of the skillsets, such as using Rifle weaponry to level up your Rifle skill level, using/building mining tools to level up your Mining and so on. There are also special abilities that can only be bought, that can make some of your base skills even more powerful, such as buying an ability that gives your bladed weapons a better chance to dismember your opponent's head/arm/leg, and much more.I could go on for quite awhile, so I'll just say.. if you aren't convinced yet, just go on Youtube and watch videos of other people playing the game. If you're into survival games, looting and base building.. or if you're into games such as Minecraft or DayZ, then chances are you'll enjoy it.Pros -- Endless replayability, whether you're playing alone or with friends.- Base building is a lot of fun, and there are a ton of blocks and such that'll allow you to create your own unique base.- RPG elements that end up mixing extremely well with the survival and base building aspects of the game, which ends up making the game incredibly addictive.- A lot of variety when it comes to items you can find in the world, and a good amount of variety when it comes to zombies, clothing, building blocks and more.- If you get bored of the main map, you can create a random map - complete with seeds - similar to Minecraft.- You can build a motorcycle once you get the right materials, making traveling the world a lot easier and faster. The better the engine, the faster it'll go, making it so the game isn't a complete walking simulator.- Too much to list, honestly. Read the TLDR version above and you'll get the gist of it.Cons -(First off, chances are these will be changed - hopefully for the better - as the game is still in early access.)- Weather system can be incredibly frustrating. You'll generally need to plan out what clothing to take with you, depending on what biome you go to. Some of the biomes are WAY too sensitive. It's not too bad once you get used to it and have the clothing you need, but it could definitely be annoying to new players, or experienced players creating new characters that are starting off from scratch.- While I don't mind this myself, some may be turned off to some of the grinding you may have to do to build concrete bases, or to find good items, such as the Auger which allows you to dig underground/collect rock and ores extremely quickly. It will take time.- Addictive! :] Which is.. bad for some people, I guess? lol."
,Recommended,251570,12743926,"Posted: 2 November, 2014",all,lazerblade,"Please note - this is an early access review.First off, let me say that I postponed reviewing this game due to having reviewed another early access game a bit too soon, and being forced to revise my review of that game because of it.Several of my friends bought into this game much earlier than I did. I held out because I'd been burned by early access before. But eventually I decided that, while 7 Days to Die was on sale, I should give it a try. So I did. I have not been disappointed.I'll list the good and bad first, then give a synopsis. Most people seem to like that kind of review style.ProsGame is currently playable and has plenty to do.Game has random world generation that is currently infinite - never run out of things to explore.Game uses voxels similar to Minecraft making everything interactive on some level.Game has hundreds of recipes for crafting.Game has farming, with 5 (soon to be 6) plantable seed types.Game has zombies to keep you on your toes, including running and fast variations.Game menu offers a wide variety of options to allow you to play the game the way you want to play it.Game has building with a wide variety of block types - make a hut, a cave or a castle, you are only limited by your imagination.Game has a wide variety of weapons with many more coming soon, from melee to projectile (clubs to guns).Game has buffs, debuffs and player attributes that must be maintained for optimal character performance. These include stamina, hunger, thirst, health, caffeine, broken bones, infection, bleeding, drowning, and several others.Game has day / night cycles with varying levels of light.Relatively low system requirements with decent framerate even on a laptop.ConsCurrently no transportation methods, so infinite world can be daunting. These should be coming in the next few months.Limited zombie types with common skins - not a lot of zombie variety (roughly 12 different types). This should increase in the next few months.Lots of bugs - some that prevent an enjoyable multiplayer experience, but most aren't game-breaking.Synopsis / SummaryHaving played over 300 hours in the past 4.5 months, I'd say I already got my money's worth out of this game. I spend a lot of time on the official forums and have gotten a good feel for how the developers and moderators react to many things. Though the players and developers do defend their game when something negative is said, it doesn't feel like a hostile conversation for the most part.7DTD is a great game, even now in its uncompleted form. I have enjoyed playing numerous hours with my son and a few friends. The focus of the game is cooperative survival, but there's definitely a place for PvP. Nothing really feels like it was tacked on as an afterthought, although many of the sub-systems within the game are or feel like placeholders.If you're looking for a destructible world where survival and sandbox gameplay mix beautifully with a zombie apocalypse, look no further. I've never played Minecraft, but as far as I can tell, this is what mature, adult Minecraft would be. If you find someone else's review that states they do not recommend the game, look at their hours. Anything less than 10 hours and they have barely scratched the surface. Anything over 40 hours and they obviously enjoyed the game enough to keep coming back.I don't like to compare games unless they have a lot in common, at least regarding play style. But as far as early access goes, 7DTD has restored my faith in indie development teams. I've never put this many hours into a game before. And I'm far from bored, or done, playing it. Go buy it, or watch some youTube videos, and see what you're missing out on."
,Recommended,251570,14246858,"Posted: 30 January, 2015",all,Max Lawless,"Don't let my 116+ hours fool you; I was playing 7 Days to Die in 2013.  Today we are at Alpha 10.4 - well over a year from initial release and I still can't get enough.   For those with a creative mind and a love of all things zombie - you may skip my review and purchase the game with confidence.  For the curious or undecided, please read on.This is a game that stands head and shoulders above all other early-access-survival offerings by far.  Unlike some of those work-in-progress titles, 7 days delivers uncommon depth and the opportunity for unlimited hours of enjoyable gameplay today.  Exciting, challenging and content heavy - you will gather, loot, hunt, farm, cook, mine, forge, craft and build as you fight to survive the zombie apocalypse.RPG elements don't overwhelm but enhance the experience and include full character customisation.  Through a clever 'wellness system' with buffs and debuffs (including clothing, armor, infection, broken bones, hunger, thirst etc.) you have a real reason to invest in your characters upkeep.   The healthier your lifestyle, the stronger you become and the longer you live.   Death - whilst inevitable - is not permanent but comes at the cost of said wellness.  Let it fall too low and as a weakling, you will struggle.Hundreds of loot types from full weapons to tools to scrap metals and seeds must be managed and stored in your custom base.  Build Fort Knox, Edinburgh Castle, an underground lair or a shed made of wood, the choice is yours and with hundreds of materials to use, you are limited only by your imagination, skill and dedication.  Keep in mind - zombies *will* pay your base a visit.Through that dedication, you will go from undressed and unarmed to being an iron clad, heavily armed killing machine, (relatively) safe in your spiked fortress.Other reasons to recommend this wonderful game include :- Tight controls- Handsome visuals- Highly customisable game options- Procedurally generated endless maps or 'Navezgane' - a prefab map- Real physics (think 'Minecraft with gravity')- Free of game-breaking bugs- Tower Defence elements- Large and growing online community- Detailed Wiki and stacks of Youtube content for the beginner- Guaranteed further development by passionate devs (Alpha 11 due late February)- Value for money!- ZOMBIEZ and SHOTGUNS!I've been a gamer since the 1980's, starting with Grundig Pong.  7 Days to Die is *the game* I've always wanted.Thank you Fun Pimps.   My rating : 9/10 (leaving 1 spare point for the completed release!)Right, I'm off to kill some zombies.Besos,Max xP.S.  If I can tack on one slightly negative comment :  Some public servers do currently contain hackers and griefers intent on spoiling your experience.  This said, it is a mostly helpful and friendly online community."
