,Recommended,251570,9013682,"Posted: 7 February, 2014",all,Angel Skyheart,"So, today I was sent a request to do a game review for a game I recently bought called 7 Days to Die. Supposedly my game reviews are famous now or something. Dunno what's up with that...Anyway, as for 7 Days to Die, I would say this game has a lot of potential. That's the thing with early access games, especially ones that are still in the Alpha stage. As it is now, the game definitely has an unfinished feel to it I think. However, with what it has now as a base, and adding on top of it the features that the game creators are planning for it? This game is really going to go far, and I can't wait to see it. That's the second reason I bought this game, the potential it has, and the potential it has is enormous.One of the coolest things about this game though is that it's the closest thing to a proper sequel to Minecraft right now. It uses the Voxel engine though so the best way I could describe it for looks would be taking Half Life 2 and making it completely destructible. Pretty amazing ne?As for the gameplay itself, that's a touch lacking, especially knowing some of the things they plan to add to the game later. Don't get me wrong, for an Alpha, it's pretty far along and pretty darn expansive, but considering the sheer amount of features they've yet to add, it's understandable why they still have the game listed as Alpha. The crafting system is really good. Some parts are a little weird, like only being able to get sticks from breaking apart bushes, rather than being able to snap off branches for sticks, and the game relies on Scrap Metal as its base staple resource for building tools, and you can only get that if you break metal things or if you scavenge for it.The game has a bigger focus on survival than Minecraft does. Zombies are currently the main enemy of the game, and they're dangerous, in that they can spawn at any time in any light source, which means even if you make it impossible for Zombies to get into your base, if you go out far enough, they will spawn in it regardless. That's one of my biggest complaints for the game currently. Minecraft did a better job by making mobs only spawn in darkness since that means there's an actual designated safe zone that you can create. In this game, currently, no where is safe, and the ambiance reflects that with some fairly creepy music and the sound of a guy whispering in a cult-ish voice that echoes on the wind(yes that's a word now). The game is also going to have a story, but it hasn't really been implemented yet. I'm guessing the whispering is going to have something to do with it, thought it's any guess what it is, since scattered news papers on the ground talk about everything from epidemics to nuclear war for the cause of this post apocalyptic world.Let's see... as for anything I don't really like about this game... I already mentioned the Zombies spawning no matter what... they can break through anything you can, but that's a deliberate game mechanic... I'm not so fond of the food/water/stamina system... I realize it's also for survival, but currently water can only be carried in jars that are consumed when you drink them, which is really really annoying. Hopefully this game will have an equipable canteen and food satchel, cause right now, water takes up half my inventory and food is difficult to come by, unless you find a corn field, but raw food like corn hardly feeds you. I don't know about you, but I'd feel pretty full after eating three corn cobs let alone 15.Oh there is one other thing I really dislike, but this is more of a glitch than anything I hope and will get fixed soon. If you ever get this game, do yourself a favor and stay away from corn fields, or at least get in and get out if you want the corn and seeds. Entities such as yourself, zombies, and animals break resource plants when they walk on them. I can't tell you how annoyed I was when the game suddenly started lagging like crazy because a bunny and a couple of stags decided to spawn in the middle of a corn field and run around AT THE SAME TIME. I think the only reason my game didn't crash is because my computer is ridiculously high end. Nevermind the fact that I had enemy spawning turned off. If zombies had been in that mess shambling everywhere and chasing the animals through the corn field, wrecking things themselves... ugh...But yeah. Other than that, this game is looking really good. I really hope they implement a way to stop zombies from spawning in certain areas soon though, cause until that happens, I don't really like playing the game with enemy spawning on, which kind of takes away from the challenge of the game itself.Huh. Just thought of something interesting. In all honestly, the best zombie survival game I've ever played is a flash game called Rebuild and Rebuild 2 (The sequel is actually better than the first. Surprising ne?) In that series, Zombies don't just spawn anywhere. They have a designated spawning zone, since some dumb cultists opened a portal to a Nether world and Zombies pour out of it. Sometimes there'd be more than one portal, and since the game setting is that of a town you have to utilize your survivors to be able to take back and defend, the town is surrounded on all sides by a forest, and there are other towns with portals open so Zombies come from those towns as well, and thus coming from the edges of the map. If they implemented THAT particular system for 7 Days to Die, that would be awesome. Like, when the world is first created, each area has a set number of Zombies, and as time goes on more come in from Death Portals as well as the borders of the map! That way instead of just survival, the game will have a somewhat clear set of objectives and goals. After all, humans as a rule don't want to just survive, we want to thrive!"
76561198016756518,Recommended,251570,16737242,"Posted: 27 June, 2015",all,soulMUNCHA,"In short this game is made up of bits and pieces of a few other games already out there. However, the manner in which these elements have been put together alone is worthy of its own praise. By that I mean, what the guys over at The Fun Pimps have done is not copy some other games base ideas and mash them all into one game, but rather have taken those concepts and sculpted them into their own unique ideas and blended them into 7 Days to Die to create a would be master piece(I say ""would be"" for now, cause it's still in alpha).Second Reason this game is awesome is the fact the the Devs(The Fun Pimps) behind this game are hard working and dedicated to making this game work. (Do your self a favour and just look up where this game started compared to where it is now). On a support level these guys get a solid A+ in my opinion aswell, their support team is constantly on the ball and working to help sort your in-game problems out.All in all  to anyone who enjoys an open world/survival/sandbox/zombie/pure gold right in your face adventure just fecking buy it type games. This is the game for you.""JUST DO IT!!"" ~ Shia Lebeouf*Disclaimer: This game is still in ""Early Access"" so expect a few bugs here and there, but trust me you wont regret buying this game :D (Time of review Alpha 11.6)"
