,Recommended,251570,10905200,"Posted: 28 June, 2014",all,Weldon,"TLDR: 7d2d is, thankfully, one of those early access games that, while somewhat buggy, is extremely playable. This is the game I always wanted Minecraft to be, and is the best of the zombie survival games to date. For why I feel this way, continue reading ;)This is how I see the game _Right Now_. I am not taking into account what the devs are planning to do, the game's potential, or any other such garbage. This is what you can expect right when you download the game, today.I almost passed on this game. I'm burnt out on minecraft, early access games, and unfinished poorly excecuted zombie apocalypse survival games in general. Thankfully, I didn't pass on it, and picked up the 2 pack to play with my wife. 7d2d has given us a lot of fun, and has overall been a pleasant experience. While occasional bugs and unexplained deaths did occur, they were never so frequent as to interfere with our ability to enjoy the game.Usually, when my wife and I play a game like this, we end up getting to a point where the pve is no longer a threat, so we turn to building bigger and better things. With this game, however, there's so many options for customizing the gameplay, that once it's no longer a threat on default settings, we can crank the difficulty way, way up, and extract more fun from the game that way, instead of building giant houses and stuff until I discover how effective pipe bombs are at making her latest monument to boredom go away. (Holy run-on Batman! Quick, get the grammar nazi reppellant!) On that note, I'll spare you from further rambling with a nice little list.The Good:-Excellent Atmosphere and tension.-Extensive Crafting.-Loads of fun with friends.-Built in challenges, without smacking you over the head and saying, ""Oh look, if you beat me instead of hiding in your little hole, I'll give you an achievement."" (The supply drop is an excellent mechanic.)-Zombies will make you afraid of the dark.-Extensive customization options. Want a hardcore mode? check. Want turbo zombies? check. Want hundreds of zombies that are as dangerous as baby seals? check. Infinite day/night? check. Pvp on/off? check. Create the experience and challenge that you want, not what they want you to have.-Managing your stamina, food, and water is critical to success, and not a tacked on checkbox for a survival game.-Looting takes time. (can be changed in the options)-Things make sense. Meaning, water needs to be boiled before used, meat cooked, wood is weaker than rock, etc.-The smell/scent system is well done, and a very enjoyable mechanic.The Bad:-Zombie Dogs.-Zombie Dogs early game, when you have no weapon.-Most of the bugs I ran into were with the dedicated server client.-Pathfinding and AI still needs work. (Allegedly this will be improved in an upcoming patch.)-Occasionally difficult to find the crafting recipe you need.-Random death for no apparent cause. This happened to me several times, and while it's entirely possible/likely that I died from something that I overlooked, if that's the case, it should be made far more apparent in the UI than it is now.-Most of the time upon killing a crawling zombie, the model will stretch/distort in a bizzarre fashion, leaving it difficult or impossible to loot.-The sound effects could be better. (I swear the sound effect the zombie dog uses when hit is the same sound a gnoll makes when getting hit in everquest.)-Dirt blocks break into octahedra (2 pyramids put together,) which just feels a little ackward, and makes it so that judging block size and distance requires practice.-You have to set all your options (graphics, sound, etc) before you join a game, as once you have, your 2 options are either ""quit"" or ""suicide.""-Zombie dogs.In conclusion, if you're on the fence about this game, or if survival games are your thing, do yourself a favor and pick this one up, it's worth it."
