76561198006978422,Recommended,251570,9328378,"Posted: 3 March, 2014",all,>TMMM<TheDaySnorer,"I hate zombies.  Such an overworked and over used idea.  If I want to see mindless creatures shuffling round doing nothing but consuming I will go into town on a saturday.  I dont do zombie films, books or TV.Or games, until now.  I was intrigued by 7 Days' strange blend of survival FPS (I am a *HuGE* Fallout 3 fan) and a weird kind of similarity to tower defence, another genre which I love.Basically the premise of the game is that some unspecified Global Disaster has happened.  Nuclear, biological AND probably a meteorite strike.  End of the world.  The game starts with you standing somewhere in the Navezgane National Park (I have no idea if this is a real place.)  The park is big enough to incorporate several types of geography, so you might find yourself on a snowy hill or in a sun blasted desert. or thick pine forest.  You quickly find things to explore (cars, bags and piles of trash, etc) and that objects you collect can be crafted (collect rocks, they can be crafted into stone).  You ALSO notice that the clock is ticking.  If the game is set to a 50 minute day/night cycle that means roughly 1 minute of game time passes for each second of real time.  This is IMPORTANT, as we will see laer and you will find out directly.  Move fast, keep searching and collecting and checking what you can craft.  And keep looking for somewhere to hole up for the night.  And look HARD, because when night falls (about 9pm game time) all hell breaks loose, quite literally.Which brings me on to the zombies.  There are several different sorts of varying types and each has a different profile.  Hints:  Some can climb and others are TOUGH; watch out for dead guys packing a bit of weight and finally, dont take on a frozen lumberjack using your fists...  Despite everything the zombies are their usual shambling selves and can usually be avoided (by running off) or by killing (re-killing?) them.  In the day.  As soon as it gets dark these swine start to MOVE and if they detect you they home in on you like wasps around a jam jar.  So be ready by the time night falls because the dark is a cold lonely and looooong place, even at one minute passing per second!Playing alone is a real challenge, especially the first day or so.  The best I have managed so far is to build myself a small island and keep out of the way of Zed at night.  After three nights they got wise and started to wander the lake so I have taken to coming home using different routes.  Do these damn things hunt by smell?!?!?Co-op is fun (I play with my son and we managed to stake out a small are by a lake in the hills and build a pretty sturdy little caste which so far hasnt been too badly tested...)  The Zed will, if allowed, slowly beat down your defences so it pays to think about escape exits and ways to sally forth to kill them before they do too much damage.Crafting is handled very well in the game and, whilst complex and it is probably worth finding a list of all the things you CAN make to give you an idea but as you collect things, the list of stuff you could make with what you have is shown dynamically, so it's not too hard to do in-game.  Personally this is the main hook of the game for me.  Even in Falloout 3 I have felt frustrated at the lack of ability to alter, influence and create within the game environment.  In 7 Days that freedom is greatly expanded.Graphics & gameplay.  7 Days is a work-in-progress still and as such is still a little rough at the edges.  The graphics are very simple, primitive when compared to console or many PC FPS's.  I am not sure if this is an aesthetic, stylistic choice or if the graphics will change as the game develops, there have certainly been some recent changes to the look of the landscape which has become smoother and easier to move through.  Overall, the graphics are usable and any need to compare with COD or whatever fades when you are in the game.There ARE still a few bugs or idiosyncrasies in the game as-is (I am writing at V7.1).  Ovccasionally an object (usually its the same object over a whole map, for some reason) will look and act collectible but when you try to an error panel will emerge.  Most irritating, and hopefully one which will be amended ASAP, is that objects which are occluded by EVEN A TINY BIT of grass have such a tiny are of effect that it is impossible to collect or search them.  Not good with a horde of Zed on your tail...Overall, as-is, I would give this game 7/10 although if the team continue developing as they are now (there is a shopping list of planned additions and changes on the Steam store page) it would no doubt get higher as the game gets closer to fll commercial release.  As it is, it feels like as my character(s) are exploring Navezgane the world and its possibilities are opening up around them.I would definitely reccomend this game."
76561198119771640,Not Recommended,251570,21512992,"Posted: 27 February, 2016",all,Garfielf,"Some things are great, some not so much.. It's fun to play, no doubt about that. However.. The graphics aren't great, the crafting is limited, the exploration isn't fully implimented as there are not a lot of different building spawns. In addition to this, the devs are slow to add new things, if they will even update it at all.I wouldn't recommend you buy this game, at least not now."
