76561198044225330,Recommended,251570,13630218,"Posted: 26 December, 2014",all,[B³] Phyl,"Buying this game and Project Zomboid, are my two proudest achievements during this Winter Sale. I may only have a couple hours on this, but I have many hours on games similar to this, such as Rust.On to the review:7 Days to Die is an Open-World/Zombie/Sandbox/Survival/Horror game, and it is one of the greatest I have played as a gamer. I would recommend not playing this on public servers, but on a private server with one or two friends with PvE, this is because the EAC (EasyAntiCheat) is extremely buggy at times, and it also doesn't do it's job very well. But that's just meYou start off with absolutely nothing, a (almost) naked man/woman, and you must collect stones, punch grass and brush to collect grass and sticks, and craft yourself a stone axe. From here you can rummage through trash, collecting tin cans (To be turned into Scrap Iron), search for bird's nests to collect feathers and eggs, and finding more stones. If you are good with a mouse and know how to aim really well, you would most likely wish to craft a crossbow with a ton of arrows, (this is why we collect a TON of feathers.) and use this to take out some Nurse zombies, for a chance to collect medical supplies, such as painkillers, bandages, Grain Alcohol, and Blood Bags.There are so many ways you could go through playing this game, just know: Be Careful when entering barns.That phrase is just a joke between me and a couple of friends. We climbed to the second floor of a barn, and a Bloated Walker (A fat S.O.B) followed us up the ladder, his weight caused the entire barn to collapse on top of us, and I barely escaped with my life, while my friend perished, and was sincerely♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥off at the game.There are, in reality, two basic playstyles: Settler, and Nomad.I don't know much about either, so I'll just give you my experience, using the map provided in game, I tracked down my friend, and we found ourselves in a wasteland biome (one with demolished houses, or well, parts of houses, and rubbish lying everywhere. We looted as many of these shattered remains as we could, finding a Cooking Pot, and following the river that flowed to the East. We eventaully found a road and holed up in the ransacked house right beside it, we fortified it by chopping down trees and creating a two block high wall on the corners of the house, we created a campfire, and replaced the shattered, ugly windows, with new wooden windows. The home has a sink, which is where we keep our food, so the zombies cannot smell us, and during the morning we set out to loot, hunt, kill, and collect. It is basically a fool-proof setup, as long as we don't forget to store ALL THE FOOD in the container, as various meats, and stews will attract zombies to your location if you have them in your inventory. Essentially, we are undetectable, and this has made the Wastelands one of my favorite biomes in the game.The biggest problem with the game is keeping yourself well fed, and keeping your thirst levels down, once we found out how to cook using the campfire, some raw venison, some wooden planks, and some bottles of water, we dealt with the hunger problem.As for thirst, we have many spare glass jars, we fill them up at pond, a few meters away from our home base, and boil the water, for a nice, refreshing, non-deadly glass of water. This system works extremely well for my friend and I. In the morning, we set out to do a variety of tasks, such as hunting stags and pigs, to collecting stones, chopping trees, and killing zombies for their loot. At night, we hide, away from the windows, out of sight, and pray a horde doesn't come our way.The game is insanely terrifying, looting a city, jumping out of the window a noticing that, just across the street, their is a terrifying horde of zombies passing by, well, that scared the hell out of me.The game is insanely difficult, well, until you get the hang of keeping yourself fed. For me, the settler style seems much easier, the nomad playstyle, constantly moving around, never staying in the same house more than once, I find it very resource consuming.I recommend this game to whoever's wanted that Open-World/Sandbox/Zombie game, if you enjoy that, this is for you!"
