,Recommended,251570,17006894,"Posted: 12 July, 2015",all,Xili0n,"After spending so much time in this game I figured I should write a review as well.7 Days to Die has been around for a little while now and, while still in Alpha status (will that ever be lifted?), the game adds more than most 'done' games. Over the course of its existence, the game has changed around so many things that you can barely recognise the old installments.This is certainly not bad though; the game absolutely improves with each Alpha. At the time I'm writing this, we are close to A16 (currently in experimental release).So what's so great about 7 Days to Die?The pro's:+ Voxel-based construction, which is refreshingly different from block-based (i.e. minecraft). Gravity is a thing too, so make sure your base is well constructed lest it comes crashing down;+ Lots of zombies with a variety of traits. You'll get the hang of how to kill a 'normal' zombie rather quick... but just wait until you encounter a Zombie Bear;+ Looting stays fresh! Buildings can have a wide variey of items and everything is useful, be it early or late stage of the game;+ Loot is logically distributed (no chainsaw in a medicine cabinet);+ The 'default' map Navezgane is fun to play; the randomly generated maps even more so;+ an interesting skill-tree (like learning how to make concrete) which pushes you to keep working to improve your base;+ The horde nights! Every 7th day you must be ready for a rampage of running zombies of increasing difficulty;+ Zombies can and will break your base down. Got a concrete wall? Forget to repair it and they will come through at some point;+ The world is out to get you. Zombies want you dead, as do wolves, bears, snakes, hunger, thirst, disentery, indection, food poisoning, and mines and buildings that cave in due to recklesness.There's so much more to add to the above list, but I feel these are the most notable. All in all, the game adds tons of fun features to keep you occupied and never make you feel 100% secure in your little fortress.Ofcourse, the game has a few cons, too:- The game is alpha, and while it's really stable, each installment does cause one or more bugs;- The learning curve can be a bit steep if you have never played similar games. This can be fun, but also off-putting for new players;- It will take a lot to get a decent batch of guns and ammo; expect to have a bow and a club as your best friends;- The first thing you want to find is a cooking pot. No cooking pot -> almost no clean water -> you die. Similarly, there's a few items you must find at least once (like a wrench) to progress. There's a chance factor involved and it can take quite a few (in-game) days to find these.All in all, I have to give this game a solid 9, even in alpha. The reason is the constant development and support by a team that loves this game and listens to the community.If you want to play a zombie survival game / crafting and building game, with or without friends, this is your game.You have to try it!"
