76561198124176543,Recommended,251570,30483464,Posted: 12 March,all,Blue Thunderhawk,"If you like minecraft, there is a 99% probability you will like this game. Those who do not like to grind need not apply. Creativity meets zombie survival game - amazing! I am real picky with games, especially sandbox games, and for the life of me I cannot figure out why there are negative reviews of this game - and then I heard about the PS4 and xbox fiasco.I will tell you that the PC experience is awesome! A lot of the reviews I have read speak about things of which they do not understand (I think they didn't embrace the grind and develop their character to the point they saw improvements), and I will attempt to clarify:1. Poor aiming system - False! With more experience, using points to increase skill levels with archery, pistols, etc. make your player more lethal. You have to do some grinding to get to that point; also, let's be honest - the character is probably closer to you than a bonafide war hero who knows how to use every weapon and machine on the face of the earth. If you want a realistic survival game that could possibly represent you, then this is it.2. Poor graphics - Debatable - I don't think people appreciate the depth of crafting (also how each new release in alpha is fine-tuning this), and when you can literally change the face of the game, having the advanced graphics of 2017 isn't there yet. If you want the sandbox, able to change anything and depth-of-crafting experience, you might have to sacrifice a little graphics. From my perspective, the graphics are amazing as I use minecraft as a measurement. These graphics blow away minecraft. I personally have no problem with the graphics.3. Story is non-existent - What! Hello, it is a zombie apocalypse game! How in-depth could the story line get?! If you are about a story-line, then choose the final fantasy series, but then you don't have a sandbox game - do you? In fact, most any sandbox survival game's story line is going to be weak if that is what you are trying to measure it to. The storyline is what you make of it.4. Single player game is miserable and online experience is lacking - Can I give you some advice? If you are a gamer, or have friends who like to game, if you have made any friends at all in life who play video games- then get them to purchase this game, and do it together. I can see how the single player would get old - I would possibly use this to develop skills and try new things. I could also see how the online experience with strangers is rough. I have read so many reviews for all kinds of games, and guess what the reoccuring theme is - there are always a few people who ruin it for everyone. There is not a single online multiplayer game I can think of where someone isn't trying to mess with someone else. Get your friends, get them to purchase the game, make a password protected game, possibly set up a dedicated server so you can get on it anytime you want even if the others aren't on, and go wild.5. It becomes too easy when your character reaches all purple (500 to 600) - Time to get creative! Go out on every blood moon into ciites; build a fort in the middle of the city above ground, and fight every night; make it as challenging as you want to.Other: Go to the 7 days to die community, and find another group of guys who play it together. Offer to set up a map where there is a 30 days truce where your team and their team build up, make bases, gather supplies, etc. to prepare for war. Then have fun."
