,Recommended,251570,29534160,Posted: 27 January,all,SmplyFrenchToast™,"This is one of those survival games that gnawed away at the top seller list in Steam for ages. For a long time, I couldn’t understand it. I watched the videos and scoffed at the raggedy character models, the basic textures, the lumpy landscapes. Another Minecraft clone. Then I was conscripted to actually write about the thing. I soon ended up knee deep in zombies, swinging a bat at their heads, running low on ammo, before eventually escaping from my homely cabin (now in ruins) down the snowy roads. What do you know, I thought, it’s good, and know that I've had time to play it. 7 Days to Die understands what games in the survival genre strive for. Dumped in an unforgiving world, you're tasked with living; first for a day, then seven days, and then for as long as possible. The hurdles to your survival are numerous, and the tasks required to overcome those hurdles can require complete knowledge of scavenging, crafting and item use. The core appeal of a survival game, as tedious as it may sound, sees players analyze, prioritize and capitalize on threats and opportunities which present themselves in the game world. So long story short I love this game, In my eyes this game has a lot of potential in it, and the developers are taking there time with this game to make it one of the best. Sure it has it's bugs, the game is still in Alpha and it has a long road ahead of it, but if you don't mind bugs from time to time and do not care to much about graphics try the game out. Who knows it might become your new favorite zombie game."
