76561198031654264,Recommended,251570,26827126,"Posted: 23 November, 2016",all,Patouski,"Just a quick - very biased - but honest review.I first got the game... in a shameful way (if you're a gamer, you know what that means XD).  It was Alpha 4, it was blocky, incomplete, zombie-filled... HEAVEN!  I played a few hours and decided to shell out the very low cost for what has become my most played game.It's Minecraft on steroids; with Zombies and strong survival mechanics.  It may have started blocky and with bad hitboxes, glitchy structural integrity mechanics and an incomplete world / story, but it's grown into a solid contender in the Survival Horror category.It is now in Alpha 15 and the game keeps getting updated, at a reasonable pace considering the size of the team and it has changed and evolved by leaps and bounds in the 2 years it's been in Early Access.  The Dev team is very active and open / accessible to the community.This game offers solid crafting and base-building mechanics, with realistic structural integrity as well as a fully destroyable voxel-based world.  You can either play a random generated world or the ""soon to have a story"" Navezgane map, which both offer very different gameplay options and the replayability is very real.The survival aspect is now getting more complex with every major update, with more and more environmental buffs / debuffs; a wellness (HP / Stam) system that is affected by several factors such as environmental debuffing; combat debuff; food quality and death.The skill system got overhauled recently, making it more complete and giving you a sense of achievement whenever you reach a milestone, rather than simply being able to do just everything from the get-go, you now have to unlock certain crafting recipes through books and / or skills combined.As for the Zombies.  The FPS aspect of the game has gotten much better over the updates, despite still suffering slightly from Alpha ""un-optimization"", it has come around from being unable to fight a single zombie next to a wall without hitting said wall 99.9% of the time, to being able to fight off dynamically randomized feral hordes on every 7th night (hence the game's name).Despite having no Workshop support, modding and modders are quite real and able to make this game even better.  The ease with which even the less-than-geek player can modify his game and gameplay through editing of .xml files, makes this game unique in itself.  You hate getting stunned? Mod it out!  You're not a Dog Lover? Mod it out! You want to be the very best... like no one ever was?  Euh... there's no Pokémon here, sorry.  Well, not yet.  XDNow, my review scores (did I say it was going to be a short one? Oops!):Graphics: Unity-based, still getting refined and optimized. Some glitches, graphics options still somewhat limited but getting there.Score: 7.5/10Gameplay: Still plagued by latency issues online, but decently solid in Singleplayer, with little truly gamebreaking bugs (it is Early Access still though, so they may happen).Score: 8.5/10Survival / Zombie aspects:  Strong, and getting stronger survival mechanics.  Skill-based system still getting refined as the game evolves.  Decent selection of Zombies for a good variety of challenges, mostly early-game, but needs more ""meat"" for late-game.Score: 7.5/10Crafting / Base-Building:  More complex mechanics getting worked on such as Generators for electricity and very realistic structural integrity mechanics already in place.  Strong variety of items and blocks to build with; making for an unlimited and very imagination-friendly building system - and there's more coming in every update!Score: 8.5/10Multiplayer aspect: Still being optimized graphically, the netcode is still to be worked on; it wasn't design as an MMO / MP game to begin with, but it has the strongest replayability value in MP - especially with random generated maps on a decent public server or privately owned servers.  Playing with friends... there's nothing like it when facing several levels of randomly spawned feral hordes.  Hilarity and Rage quitting can happen - be warned.  ;)Score: 8.5/10Final words:The game isn't perfect.  I find myself ♥♥♥♥♥ing at it sometimes, but obviously The Fun Pimps did something good, as I racked up well over 2100 hours on Steam and shelled the well-deserved and very affordable 20$ (CDN) at the time for a game that simply keeps getting better.  It may not be your cup of tea, but if you do play - do not hesitate to give it a chance - do not judge after only 10 minutes, or even less than an hour - because this game grows on you."
