76561198058337162,Recommended,251570,30336972,Posted: 5 March,all,THOT B GONE,"I decided to play until night 7 before writing a review, because I figured that the game is called ""7 days to die"" for a reason. I'll be chronicalling my experience with the game and the defenses I designed, so if you don't want to read all that crap just skip to the end of the review. Otherwise, enjoy.To sum it up, you have an initial 7 days to build a base complete with fortifications to stave off a mega horde that appears on the night of the Red Moon (or blood moon) which rises every 7 nights. All the zombies in the Red Moon Horde are fast and dangerous, so building up defenses is imperative if you want to survive.I spawned many times, died many times too before I could even get to the 7th day, but eventually I wised up and started playing within my own limits. The Bow and Arrow is probably the best early game weapon available until you find a gun. It's easy to build, and if you can aim a headshot you can dispatch most Zed in one hit. I suggest building one as soon as you can if you want to get far. Melee combat is simply too risky, especially if you are fighting dogs or other fast enemies, but I digress.I established myself on a flat part of the desert near a camp that I later disassembled for materials. I built a very small wooden house with a bed and storage box, then proceeded to dig ditches 3 blocks and 2 blocks wide approximately 3 meter from my house. I lined the inner edges with gravel and topped the gravel with barbed wire, then inside the ditch near the rim I placed log spikes for extra damage. Inside of the ditch parameter I dug a ditch that was 1 block deep, 2 blocks wide, and 6 blocks long which I filled with log spikes. I placed these ditches on the left, right, and back side of my house leaving the front of the inner courtyard somewhat exposed. More on that later.Approximately 3 meters from the first ditch I began digging more ditches. Each ditch was 3 blocks deep and 1 block wide, and every 2 blocks I would leave as a small path so the Zed could cross (part of the plan I assure you). Each path was a 2x2 land bridge that I filled in with wooden spikes. I then dug larger 3x3 holes that were 4 blocks deep in between the land bridges to perhaps catch stragglers. My intention was for the outermost parameter to act as a buffer zone, trapping or slowing the horde and potentially lowering their numbers before they reached the inner ditch. In between the two ditches I dug similar 1x2x6 ditches that I filled with log spikes to do even more damage and further thin the horde.I then placed explosive barrels in between the land bridges. My intention was to funnel the undead and kill them en masse with the explosive barrels being detonated by carefully aimed shots from a pistol that I had found with a full magazine.All of my preparations were done with very scarce resources since my fortress was built in the middle of the desert and I had to travel very far to reach trees that were ample with wood. I had to manage both time, food, and supplies while also fighting off roaming undead and making sure to pay regular visits to the nearby river to cool off in the desert heat, since despite not wearing any clothes save for a cloth hat I was almost always burning hot in the baking sun of the plains.On the fateful night that the Red Moon arose over the horizon, as lightning flashed all around me, I prepared the last of my defenses. Wooden spikes and barbed wire surrounding my entire house, even going so far as to cover the walls in barbed wire, and next to that, another 1x1 trench dug around the entire house right next to the foundation was filled with log spikes, then surrounded itself with barbed wire fencing and wooden spikes, with more wooden spikes being placed blocking the only opening in the parameter. The horde came, and I sat atop my house that was 4 blocks high.This was, obviously, where things took a very bad turn for the absolute worst. Apparently the zed are smarter than I anticipated, as nearly all of them simply dodged all of my defensive traps and made for the weakest part of my wall, the opening that I blocked. None of them fell in the deep holes that I had dug, and they all came from separate directions in very small number, but very quickly. Absolutely none of them fell into the drap ditches, nor did they bother with the walls I had erected, nor the barbed wire or wooden spikes. The only thing they broke were the wooden spikes that I used to temporarily seal the front exit. They broke through them rather easily. I couldn't fire a single bullet when one of them darted up my 4 block high house and started attacking me.What's the point in even building defenses if the zed will just run right around them? They're suppose to be mindless man-eating animalistic savages. They aren't suppose to think about dodging traps and defenses and pits. I was sadly very disappointed. It was such a fun game. Building the fortress was the best part, yet it was all for not as my carefully planned out traps, pits, and hazards were completely averted by every single Zed.///////////////////SHORT REVIEW HERE\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\It's a really fun game, with really good core mechanics. The kind of game that you could spend hours on either alone or with friends building epic bases and headshotting fat zombified cops as they helplessly waddle towards you.The crafting menu is one of the best I've ever seen. you can seemlessly access recipes by clicking on certain ingredients, which will show you only the things that the specific ingredient is used in, or you can view every item in the game at once, or you can view different types of items. It's very well organized and very well executed.It performs well enough. On ultra settings it looks very basic. While that can't be helped, the game simply overshadows that by giving you enjoyable gameplay that you can truly get lost in.The only thing I daresay that kills it, is the poorly executed 7 day horde defense mechanic that pits very fast, very dangerous enemies again potentially under-equipped survivors, and while I've never been one to condemn a game punishing players who fail to prepare, it seems that even with diligent preparation the horde is simply too much to fight.If I can say one thing about this game, it is that it lives up to it's name. It's not just a catchy title or a witty one liner to attract the masses. It's more akin to a brief description, or a warning perhaps. Truly, you do have 7 Days to Die.I would absolutely recommend this game."
