76561198035612819,Recommended,251570,26081854,"Posted: 16 October, 2016",all,T-Brock,"Memorable 7 Days experiences:My first zombie kill:I had just crafted my very first stone hatchet. It was a beautiful piece of crap. As I marveled at my creation, I looked up and saw a lone walker shambling along looking mostly harmless.  I decided that this would by my first brawl with the undead. I collected my wits and charged toward my foe intent on hacking it to pieces. Blow after blow and attack after attack was traded as we grappled with each other in a lethal embrace. Finally I gained an advantage as one of my blows stunned the zombie. I capitilized on the opportunity and I continued to beat it down until finally the zombie fell to the ground, dead. I congragulated myself on my first victory in battle until slowly the zombie got back up to its feet and proceeded to march towards me again. Startled yet determined to secure my first kill, I swung my hatchet at its head over and over again. We once again traded blow after blow, attack after attack until I finally stunned the zombie again. I kept up my attack until finally it fell to the ground dead for the second time. Relieved, I wiped the sweat off my forehead from the trying encounter and realized the danger that I was in. These zombies are tough. As my thoughts trailed off to contemplate the difficulties of this game and what I would need to do to survive, the zombie, twice dead already, pushed its dead body up and came at me for a third time. ""This can't be happening,"" I thought as I hacked and hacked at the zombie. Once again it got stunned and fell dead to the ground, but this time I didn't stop. I kept swinging and swinging and swinging and swinging until finally the body bust into bones and entrails. I kept swinging and swinging and swinging and swinging. Then the bones and entrails burst into a blob of gore. I knew it wouldn't get up this time, but I kept swinging and swinging and swinging until the blob of gore dissapeared entirely. This entire time I had been screaming irl. My friend and I looked at each other and were like, ""Damn.""10/10 would♥♥♥♥♥♥pants again.My first horde night:This was my seventh night. I had found a house on the first day and renovated it. I had built a trench around the front porch and protected the entrance with wood walls and a wood door. The trench was completely filled with wood spikes and my plan was to stall the zombies on the wood spikes long enough to shoot them with a bow and kill them. At 21:30 the sky turned blood red, undoubtedly foreshadowing my eminent death. I stood on the porch with a grand total of 150 stone arrows, defiantly determined to hold off the incoming horde that was famished for my flesh. At 22:00 the music played and the zombies spawned. Within moments five plus zombies were already wading through my wood spikes. I shot wildy into the dark as my candles did little to illuminate my targets. This was all in vain because by 22:30, two zombies had already broken into my first door and rushed me on the porch. I fired one arrow in their direction before they reached me. Within seconds I was stun locked and dead. This was going to be a long night. I respawned near my bed and ran for my life. I topped the first hill to see my house dimly lit by my 5 measly candles. I sprinted towards the front door. I dodged and weaved past sprinting zombie and sprinting zombie and finally made it to my front door. I quickly fumbled with the door and threw it open then I spun around as quickly as I could, and slammed it into the face of the entire horde that had been chasing me, nearly 10+ zombies. I hurried to the middle of the room, threw the door open to the safe tunnel that I was building, and rushed in. I opened the hatch and climbed down the ladder, down into the tunnel that I was carving out of the mountain. The plan was to dig a deep enough hole to eventually dig a tunnel out to the side of the mountain. That way if a horde broke through, you could just lead them through your tunnels and you could escape, unscathed. A ""if all else fails,"" plan. Well this tunnel was not yet finished. I had gotten down to my desired depth, but I still needed to dig out to the side of the mountain. Finally I reached the bottom and I crept around the corner and hid behind two base wood frames. Not even upgraded yet. I crouched and I listened hopelessly as the horde cried out for my flesh and tore apart my house in their attempts to get me. I assessed my situation. All I could do was wait. All my resources were upstairs and my loot bag was outside on the porch where they had first killed me. I had no time to grab it on the way in. During my mad dash to the house, I had taken a few hits from the surrounding zombies and my grand 17 hp didn't do much to bolster my confidence about the situation. While I continued to think about how bad my situation was, time began to pass. It hit 5 AM. One hour to go and this horrid night would be over and the zombies would stumble out of my house, unaware of my presence. 6 AM! Finally. The night is over. I wait for the zombies to leave. The sounds of wood breaking apart stops. The hideous snarls and growls all cease. They lose track of my scent as I lay hidden at the bottom of a damp hole. I hear some stumble outside. Then I see him... ""Zombies can climb ♥♥♥♥ing ladders! WTF??? Why!"" I bemoan as I watch the lone walker float down the ladder, not even utilizing the grips, or even facing the ladder for that matter. Despite the hilarity, I'm still in shock and fear as I wish the walker to return up his ladder and out of my house to where he came from. I lay still behind my wood frames, which are transparent. The zombie still doesn't see or sense me. He climbed back up the ladder and I heaved a sigh of relief. Until he came down again. Followed by a friend of his. I know I'm dead now. They're gonna block each other from going up and they'll eventually walk around the corner and find me. I sit there for a minute waiting for the inevitable, torn between wanting it over as quickly as possible and wishing that they'd both somehow find a way out of the house that didn't include munching on my innards. My wishes held no bearing on reality as the first zombie began to stiffly walk in my direction. He soon found me and tackled me to the ground and bit at my stomach tearing out my intestines and splattering my blood upon the walls. His friend shuffled in and took his place at the buffet de me.10/10 would be buffet again.7 days is amazing. Mainly due to its incredible AI that will literally hunt you no matter where you are and no matter what you do. You will never be able to put up enough walls or enough wood spikes, because when horde night comes you will most likely die many many times before you can successfully survive one. This game is not for the faint of heart. If you can't handle dieing over and over again then this game is not for you. But if you enjoy truly being scared for your life and you enjoy a really challenging experience then this game is definitely that."
