,Recommended,251570,33575468,Posted: 15 July,all,Docdra,"A game that gets better and better as time goes by - in fact, one of the few EA games that is totally enjoyable right now, with AAA-like features.   It may not be the prettiest zombie survival game out there, but between the crafting, world generation, sense of foreboding, etc. this game has pretty much all others in the genre beat.I haven't experienced any game breaking bugs, but have experienced a few issues with getting caught in doorways.  For some reason I sometimes get bumped into the air and end up stuck on top of doors.  It has only happened 4 times in almost 50 hours of play and I can usually get out be destroying the door beneath me, but it can be a pain if it happens when zeds are nearby.  Other than that, no other bugs to report at this time.++Pros++- Real sense of foreboding at night- A deep crafting system- Lots of replayability with randomly generated worlds- Nice variety of zombies/enemies- Very active devs- Very good price point considering what you get--Cons--- While the learning curve isn't exactly steep, it can be a pain to get a good start (do some research)- Zombies can seem a little too prescient with the heat map system the devs have in place- NPCs are sparse, making it seem like the only people that survived are you and traders- Farming is a bit of a joke - gather plants, make one seed from one plant, plant seeds, get exactly the same number of plants from seeds planted - in other words, you don't get multiple seeds from one plant, thus you never get ahead which makes farming a waste of time and very unrealistic"
76561197978334641,Recommended,251570,33632983,Posted: 18 July,all,[LT3] Cookie,1127 Hours in now since first release years ago and this is my first review.Never have I played a game that has recieved so much love from it's development team over such a great span of time.  This latest release has got to be it's finest so far.  As far as survival goes this game rewards the prepared... and by being prepared you really have to think out your objectives for each mission and supply yourself appropriately otherwise you WILL regret not having done so.  Too many games have tailored and adjusted their dynamics to appease the mellinial mentality where kids want immediate gratification for minimal effort.   Back in the day games pushed you to work for what you have...  this game has definitely tapped into this and I applaud the devs for doing so.  Most of the deaths i've experienced i can usually sit back in my chair and think... yeah that was stupid of me.  Its not to say you cant get away with pushing the limmits... this comes with it's rewards also.  But if you neglect mutiple factors while pushing for the prize you will regret it... either by dehydration or lack of stamina where a vulture's pesky attack finally finnishes you off because you failed to prepare for such an encounter.  Ok cant wait to play another round... see ya!
,Recommended,251570,30639856,Posted: 20 March,all,NardoLoopa,"Version A15:If you thought Minecraft lacked purpose and danger, and Fallout 4 phoned in base building, then this is the game for you.7D2D offers several games in one:- When you have no idea how the mechanics of the game work, it offers the pleasure of trial and error (aka death), in a survival scenario.  Can Zombies climb ladders?  Am I safe up here?  And all the mechanics are discoverable without a wiki.  Except this: mushrooms need to be planted in chess-board fashion.- It also provides a nice string of progressive needs and satisfactions: can't find drinkable water? look for a pot; night vision is an issue? make a mining helmet; always hungry?  Start a farm.- Eventually you'll dominate the environment.  At this point you can play Minecraft during the day, and fend off hordes at night.  But the game has a second stage . . .  Starvation Mod!- Starvation Mod is basically hard-mode.  However, it pulls off a rare trick: even at late stages you can't dominate the environment to the point of boredom.  Where 7D2D Vanilla kept me interested for at least 60hours, Starvation Mod extended that to over 250.  250 game days and I still had things to do in game; quests to achieve; problems to solve; dangers I still had to run from.- Then there's the brutally hard True Survival mod.  It's an exercise in masochism.  After 70hrs, I found my limit.I think my favorite part of the game is time-management.  Not like some stopwatch, but just an eye on the clock.  Can I loot this house and still get back to base?  At a certain time of night the Zombies start running.  I've spent more than a few nights in a panic-room, still as a mouse, hoping the Zed would stop banging on my door, and lose interest.  Crap, I forgot it was day 7 . . ."
