,Recommended,251570,25590579,"Posted: 19 September, 2016",all,chooseareality,"This is the one game I own that I keep coming back to and playing again and again. It is also what I consider my most successful Early Access purchase. TFP (Team Fun Pimps) has consisently delivered on continuous updates and improvements as they approach feature complete on this fine game.Don't get me wrong. It is certainly still an EA (Early Access) title and every major release comes with a new collection of bugs and issues as TFP works to make the game into the vision they had years ago when they started this. They are however quick to fix the bugs with quick patches after each major release.For the current price, $25, I would strongly recommend this game if you like zombies, survival games, and crafting in a voxel world (Minecraft with better graphics) where every 7th day hordes of zombies will attack each and every player in the world (This is new as of the pending alpha 15 release, it used to be just one horde I think, but I don't play multi-player).I have 285 hours on record right now. That number is a bit high because of walking away on pause, but I would easy say I have spent 150 hours on a game that only cost me $25 and still has a ton of promise and is being actively developed by a great team of developers.My only caveat is please don't buy this if you want a done game. Wait another half year or so for beta or actualy release if you don't understand that EA means bugs and shifting gameplay as the real game is molded through easy iteration. You will be happier and the forums and boards won't be clogged up with toxic posts about things that aren't even supposed to be done yet.There is also a console version now. It is made by a different company, TellTale Games, and is very close to a full release behind at this point. TFP is focused on the PC version and they leave the step child console version to TellTale. I would avoid it and just go with the PC version if you ever slightly prefer PC games."
