76561197978155502,Recommended,251570,25520915,"Posted: 15 September, 2016",all,brianmi,"7 Days is a fun game, but there's reservations ahead.  Hard to imagine a game that is still in ALPHA after nearly 3 years of being available (!), but that is 7 Days.There's lots that works in this game that makes it a fun experience:1. If you're not a graphics snob, the scenery is quite good, with varying environments, and some weather effects add to the realism.  But it is repetitive quite a bit, maybe 20-30 hours and you've seen it all unless you just hunkered down mostly being a noob.2. The crafting system is SUPERB.  It's logical, decently progresses to hold interest even for experienced players and most of the items, outside of items to build unique or accurate looking buildings, are useful in the game somehow.3. You can have lots of adventures, many's the times I've barely made it to safety before darkness or had to use my wits to survive or overcome, recover a minibike at a distance, or got caught somewhere and had to be quickly creative.4. You can choose your survival approach for a safe home: dig tunnels, build a base, take over a building.  You can be nomadic, or build the Taj Mahal and raise crops.  The flexibility is nice.5. There's a fair amount of replayability as I still enjoy spawning somewhere new, and seeing how quickly I can get myself up to a crossbow or minibike, whichever comes first.6. There's a decent variety of zombie's though it won't take too long and you'll know them all, hating the dogs worst of all if a pack of them catch you out in the open.7. Patches seem to show up about every 2 months or so so the developers are still at it, but based on progress rate, and the fact that they consider this much of a developed release still an ALPHA, it could easily be a couple years until it might be done.  Don't get it expecting fast progress as slow and steady is more the word.8. It's been very stable for me, runs without crashing and has been more than a year since getting stuck somewhere unable to move.  750GTX video runs it well on quad core 3.4Ghz.There are frustrations though.a. AI is not the best, zombie's just plod at you relentlessly though are good at finding a path to you when available, won't give it away since you'll likely realize it before long, but there's a straightforward means to survive the 7 day routine of attacks that the developers really should work on making not so obvious (SPOILER SKIP TO NEXT LINE: ........think up, most zombie's can't...)b. Climate often overheats an area too much and can cause you to move sluggish, this needs nerfing as it seems too often, or, drains you too quickly/unrealistically.c. Locating Book schematics you need to craft certain objects gets a little old and pretty frustrating as you enter your 4th bookstore, search all the shelves and still can't get a recipe for a crossbow, but have had 10 on them for crafting a pistol or somesuch.  In fact, in all my gameplay, have only had the Riddle of Steel book once.d. There are other items that you'll rarely ever get to assemble without considerable time in the game, like a machine gun, AK-47, 44 Mag.  You may try and collect the parts, but my experience is you'll sooner find one in a loot crate dropped into the game than come up with all the parts AND book, so that's a bit frustrating.e. The game desperately needs a story and deeper goal than just survive.  That is, there are no boss monsters, final solutions to reach OZ or anything like that which would raise the game to a whole new level.  The developers seem deaf to all suggestions made by the community to act on this.  Their answer was to add mini-quests to the game, but the excitement wears off quickly on those.f. Once you have a mini-bike, you'll quickly feel that you've won the game as there's not much left to do, other than grind away killing zombies and grow corn (i.e. collect resources for no real purpose), but by that point you're most certainly beyond any risk from the zombies.  That's when you'll be wishing there was a story, somewhere you had to get on the minibike that was hard to find / get to, and something to do now that you're adequately armed, but alas, you can only ride around endless roads to endless mini-towns and occasional cities that quickly start looking and feeling the same.So dear reader, it's a fun game, has some replayability if you're the type that would enjoy that early escalation from primitive to set up a secure base, but ultimately like so many of these games (Empyrion, ARK, Minecraft) you always end up asking yourself sooner or later based upon how quickly you can progress; what is the point of continuing to stack some resource in some chests for someday that never comes... (with apologies to the ARK bosses which are a possibility in multi-player, but not so much in single player)."
