76561198094029672,Recommended,251570,26146876,"Posted: 21 October, 2016",all,That One Guy,"I'll try to cover this review from a potentially new player's perspective.7 Days to Die is a game about exploring, scavenging, crafting, building, and fighting zombies (and possibly players).Currently, this is an open world game with no main objectives or ways to ""win"" the game. There are, however, side quests/objectives that can be fulfilled for gaining ""skill points"".Skill points are awarded from leveling up in the game, or from completing objectives. These points can be spent to improve the players passive abilities in the game. For example, increasing Archery would allow the player to deal more damage to targets via bows.A main feature about this game is that at 22:00 on every 7th Day, a zombie horde spawns nearby the player, and knowing where the player is, will continuously hound the player until 6:00 the following day. Hordes become progressively harder as time lingers on.Combat can be difficult early on in the game, but after one progresses, combat can become very easy (Something that I believe needs balancing).A few tips I'd give to new players are:1) Avoid jumping from heights higher than 5 blocks, lest you sprain or break your leg.2) Don't feed the bears. Especially not the zombie bears. They're only hungry for you. If you're not sure what a zombie bear is, you'll know the difference as soon as you see one.3) You're not safe in or across water. Zombies move underwater like Barbossa's cursed crew from PotC.4) Learn what an Air Filter Land Mine looks like.5) Building a pillar into the air to avoid a zombie isn't effective, because unlike Minecraft, gravity is (somewhat) existent in 7 Days to Die.6) Headshots deal much more damage to zombies than bodyshots.7) Maybe play around in creative mode first, just to see what different weapons are like, or what the different building block strengths are. Or, if you want to see how many explosive gas barrels it'd potentially take to blow up a building, you could do that too.The game is resource intensive on one's computer. 6GB of free RAM is recommended, meaning if your PC has 8GB RAM installed, consider closing out other programs before running 7 Days to Die.I believe that this game has come a long way in development, but it still has quite a ways to go. There's still a few more bugs to squash, balancing changes that need to be made, and content that should be added. I'm almost certain that it'll reach completion... someday (we all know it's been a while already).Currently, I'd rate the game at 8/10, though this could be slightly generous.I think the game is worth its price."
