76561198092531965,Recommended,251570,11679900,"Posted: 12 August, 2014",all,skylinedive1205,"I am pleasantly surprised at this game. It's outstanding, especially for an Alpha. If the game stayed as-is, I would be happy playing it for a long time. I was looking for a ""builder"" game when I came across this title. The problem I have with builder games is that most do not have an immediate sense of danger. Think Sim City: you build and build... but whats the goal? Other than maintaining your city, with a few disasters, it doesn't seem dangerous enough... and I want to fly down the highway to the Danger Zone!I looked into DayZ and Rust before choosing this game, respectively. DayZ's focus seemed more ""Deathmatch shooter w/ scavenging gameplay"", where the real threat was that of other players. Rust does have some building to it, but it's limited to fort-like structures, and I wanted more. That and the idea of your character staying in the Rust world when you log out wasn't appealing (yes, there are server mods to change this but still). Again, the focus was more on the danger from other players. Other builder games focus on RTS or Castle Defense styles of gameplay. Though 7D2D does have defense-oriented gameplay, that's not all that there is. The focus is survival (broadly) with a very clear and present danger. The NPC threats (zombies, infected dogs, killer wasps) seriously pose a threat and should not be taken lightly. This gives me a great sense of immersion with this game. You can fortify an already established building or build one entirely from scratch, from the ground up. You do this while fighting, hiding, scavenging, while also needing to drink, eat, and rest. This is the danger I wanted. You are thrown into the game on the outskirts of the one map provided in the game. Though it's a huge map. It takes time to traverse. The dangers of starvation, dehydration, fatigue, and being a flesh-picnic are real from the moment you log. You can mine, cut trees, harvest food, create building materials, weapons, exlosives, etc. The scavenging and (some) crafting feels much like Fallout. You can play on a server with other players, working with eachother for survival or against eachother, adding more danger. I currently only play co-op with one friend or single player solo.The game already has a few options to change gameplay: longer days/shorter nights, increased/decreased zombie difficulty, damage modifiers, etc. The only problems I have run into are some storage container glitches (not opening mostly) and no drag-&-drop inventory functions; it's click to pick up, click to drop. Neither of these issues are major and do not take away from my gameplay experience what so ever. Currently, there are no options to change map, customize maps, customize characters, and so on. However, if you read the developer's notes, these changes are coming!If you're looking for an in-depth survival game where you can build and alter the very world around you; either through solo play, with friends, or many survivors; please check this game out. Our money goes towards the betterment of this already-amazing game. It's worth it. I wholeheartedly want to thank the people at The Fun Pimps for making this.Now, if you'll excuse me, I better buckle in and hold on tight... because I'm on the (cue Top Gun)... highway to the Danger Zone!"
