,Recommended,251570,29916534,Posted: 14 February,all,Mister Artorias,"I was originally skeptical about getting into this game due to my distaste of early access zombie survival games, but there are a few things about 7 Days to Die that seem to draw me in.First, the good:- In-depth crafting system that utilizes a ton of items. The crafting menu is intuitive and it comes with a handy little search bar.- Leveling up and improving skills is based on what you do in the game. For example, if you spend a lot of time mining, your mining skill will increase. There are a wide variety of skills that you can improve on, giving the game somewhat of an RPG feel.- Fully destructable environments. You can chop down trees, dig up the ground, break into buildings, and so forth.- The ""horde"" is an interesting event that occurs every 7 days in the game. The bloodmoon will rise and packs of zombies will be trying to tear your property down. This event practically makes base building and scavenging for better equipment a necessity. This might be a negative for some, but in my eyes, it gives the player an incentive to plan ahead and fortify.The bad:- The game feels quite clunky. Most of the animations aren't very fluid and don't have much weight behind them.- Building and maintaining a proper base can take a LOT of time. This is coming from someone that mostly plays singleplayer. Time spent on base management can obviously vary from different amounts of players working together.- Quite a few bugs, but nothing game breaking from my experience so far.I'm having a pretty good time on my own with this game. I've yet to have the experience of playing with another person, but I assume it would make the game a whole lot more fun."
