,Recommended,251570,28402429,"Posted: 16 December, 2016",all,Windhund,"As advertised, this is Minecraft meets Zombie Survival Horror. Still a bit rough around the edges, totally enjoyable.The PVE is genuinely difficult and there are many ways to get wounded and die. Hypothermia, overheating, sprains, bleeding out, dysentery, starvation, thirst, tripping over a cactus, and getting eaten by a bear. Weapons are few and far between. And forget guns, usually you just get parts, on the very rare occassion you'll get a pistol.There's a huge world to explore with varied buildings and terrain (although sometimes nonsensical like walking from scorching desert into snow). Sometimes you stumble on a campsite, sometimes you wander through a blasted city. The graphics aren't the greatest, but its used to good effect. Watching a sunrise, or looking up at the Milky Way at night, or seeing your home base on the horizon all lit up after days out foraging.And then there's the zombies. During the day they're slow, but it's very easy to get distracted and snuck up on. The noises they make... going into a house where you hear a zombie thrashing around upstairs is genuinely creepy. Combat is brutal, it's best to have a bow. If you go hunting, zombies can smell if you have meat on you, better cook and store your food well.And then night comes... and you can't see♥♥♥♥♥♥if you didn't thik to make a torch (animal fat cooked in a campfire into tallow combined with wood). And the zombies aren't slow any more, they move fast. It's like that first night in Minecraft, hunkered down and listening and hoping...And then on every 7th day, the zombies frenzy! EVERYTHING is destructable, even concrete, and the zombies will eventually get in. Even holed up in a prison tower, surrounded by wooden spikes, they got in. They always get in!When the night is over, you have 7 days to repair and prepare for the next frenzy.The PVE is so difficult, it's enough to make players genuinuely work together. Unlike in some other survival games where players will murder you with a rock as soon as they see you, 7 Days To Die has the proper PVE pressures to make you happy to see another human being."
76561198020554667,Recommended,251570,28396980,"Posted: 15 December, 2016",all,Sabathane,"This is one of the rare games that stays in ""Early Developement"" for way too long, has a huge problem, but then actually fixes it and is fun to play again. Most of the other reviews cover graphics/bugs/mechanics. What you need to know if you want to have fun on this game is:1. Set it on the easiest possible difficulty with the most drops, lowest zombie spawn rate, ect.2. Don't bother trying to start anywhere but the forest areas. Especially if you are in the snow, just restart.3. Work towards the forge as soon as you can, it will help you get the blunderbuss and make more iron for arrows and traps. Clay is the dark dirt with cotton growing in it, leather can be gotten from couches if don't want to chase deer/pigs.4. Make two bases. One with all your boxes and working areas, and another one specifically for defending from the hordes.  I recommend a series of cobblestone walls with barbed wire and wood spikes inbetween. Make sure to have it only be accessilble by using wooden frames, or the zombies will target the weaker entrance area."
