76561198004979129,Recommended,251570,13481688,"Posted: 20 December, 2014",all,{KOSD} Panfuricus,Lumberjack zombies chopping down your doors and zombie troll dogs devouring you. Why are you not buying this? It's hours and hours of hillariously derpy zombie fun.
76561197993030957,Recommended,251570,16431487,"Posted: 15 June, 2015",all,Lonetac,"Im well over 200 hours into this game and have loved every moment after the first initial learning curve.  Make no mistake, the begining of this game is not for everyone and it does take a plan with some knowledge of in game mechanics to be successful.  This is not dayz or lfd2.  You do not go in rambo style and kill zombies right off the bat.  It takes practice and a plan.  The begining is hard.  With that said there is so much opportunity they are recognizing adding tons of different ways to die and ways to survive.  I have owned this game for awhile and did not care for the first few Alphas but now its pretty much one of the best I have played.My GF and i have both over 200 hours in game and love the base building along with the survival / treasure hunt aspects which they are only improving on with every release.Basic premise, you start out naked and alone in the forest.  Survive... the first 20 minutes of your life are probably the hardest and it gets easier as you gain levels, make better loot, etc.  Knowing things like crafting 2-4 stone axes in the begining and checking the durability so you keep the good one can go a long way from being ""wtf this game is impossible why cant i cut a tree down"" to ""oh ok, thats how that works"".Hunting could definitely be expanded on at the time of this review there are only three animals to hunt.  Rabbit, pig and deer.  All with varying food recipes that you can make like stews and steaks.  Boiled or grilled, etc.  Farming is pretty cool and you can become self sufficient eventually (Baked potatos!!) and growing things like Coffee and Golden Rods really go a long way for making things easier.  Coffee and beer give you stamina regen allowing you to do more things without tiring for a bit while golden rod can help you level, quench thirst and regen stamina instantly.  Its knowledge of the mechanics and a small learning curve.  Once you figure it out this game is deeply rewarding.Base building is pretty good with a lot of options with the objects you can create like wood, stone, hay, dirt, etc.  The physics system is getting upgraded this next release so that will help with the destruction of things.  Its pretty satisfying building castles, houses and bases with moats and wood spikes and other defenses around protecting you from hordes.  One of my favs is placing dynamite sticks around the outside and shooting them when hordes walk by :DThere is a night and day system, the night time can be configured to have zombies be a bit quicker.  One thing about this game is they allow you to tweak or mod anything you want since its just changing a script.  Dont like the dogs?  Take them out.  Dont like the bees?  take them out.  Want more zombies, increase the spawn level.  Tons of options if you modify some .ini files plus they give quite a few tweaks in the initial world setup which you can change at anytime.  So starting out on a easier difficulty helps and once you get established increase it or increase zombie spawn levels.  They are adding weather in the next release and eventually you can freeze to death and the weather will have effects on you.  Desert making you drink more, etc.Like i said, its got a bit of learning curve but it is absolutely a blast and fun ride once you get the hang of it.  Awesome coop game if you just want to play with friends.  I anxiously await every release.  Make no mistake though, this is Alpha and you will encounter bugs.  I have yet to experience anything game breaking but we have had things like disappearing supply crates (the ones from the planes, currently was just fixed), breaking of legs too easily (also just fixed), abnormalities with the voxel system like floating water or floating land pieces, looting of animals broken.  The pimps are usually pretty good about getting them hotfixed but the game could use some polish and we all know that but its Alpha and polish is what Beta is for.  If you are not ready to play a game in Alpha then wait it out.  The forums are great for finding work arounds."
,Recommended,251570,25892737,"Posted: 6 October, 2016",all,captainxenu,It is a ton of fun if you play with your friends.
76561198285228033,Recommended,251570,34202119,Posted: 12 August,all,skagitboy,Runs better than PUBG.10/10
76561198030374042,Recommended,251570,13175641,"Posted: 30 November, 2014",all,commander515,"In a nutshell - it's like Minecraft, but with realistic zombies and a sense of urgency. Like many other people, I enjoy Minecraft, but what it lacks (at least in 'Survival' Mode) is a greater motivation to build impressive, architecturally-innovative structures other than 'it would be cool to build this'. With no friendly NPCs to recruit or roaming monster hordes with a nefarious agenda to deal with, it largely doesn't matter what you build or where you build it.Not so the case here. 7 Days To Die is the Minecraft version of the zombie apocalypse, and as such there are voxel-based destructible environments and many, many zombies. Starting out in the middle of nowhere with next to nothing is far more unsettling when there are flesh-eating zombies visibly roaming around not too far away. Whether you're playing single-player or multi-player sandbox mode (the campaign as such does not exist yet), the threat of a massive, ravening horde is ever-present. At any moment, you could find yourself surrounded by 30+ mindless undead with no other goal than to tear apart your entire shelter so that they can do the same to you. Every day of game time is a frantic rush to scavenge, craft, and build as much as possible before the sun goes down and the black of night makes the zombies nearly impossible to combat.7 Days To Die has just entered the latest phase of its Alpha Build (#10) which brought with it a large number of changes. The game does suffer from some glitches and still requires a fair amount of graphical optimization and bug fixes. That being said, it is still very stable and playable at this point. The game is very well-designed and keeps getting substantial gameplay improvements with every new update. This is certainly a zombie survival game that provides a significant challenge even into the late stages, as the hordes grow in size and lethality by adding more, and more dangerous, zombies that can pose a threat to even the strongest shelters, if not properly defended. It is well worth picking up, even in the current Alpha state, if you are a fan of zombie survival and Minecraft-style harvesting/crafting games."
,Recommended,251570,23603176,"Posted: 16 June, 2016",all,HappyBiscutz,"Let's face it: Early Access is a bad idea. You end up paying too much for a game that simply isn't worth the money, and likely will be abandoned before it is, or take a decade to be ""released"" but not finished.Well I'm happy to say I've actually found this game worth more than I paid. For an Alpha stage game it is very well developed and polished. To be honest this game (with maybe some graphics upgrades and a camera glitch when you die patch) could be ""released"" (out of early access) and I wouldn't be cross at all. It is single handedly the best Early Access game you'll ever pay for, and here is why:Eating, Drinking, Temperature are just as important as in Don't Starve if not more, giving you objective play.Crafting is simple and easy to use, alot like Rust's system, with blueprints for a few end game items.Building is similar to Minecraft, except this game does have physics, so build support beams! (That's fun too!)Diseases, Infections, and other status conditions are alot like DayZ, except they are actually implemented in this game.Combat is difficult (as in risky without the right tools and tactics) just as it would be realistically, and by that same rule the game is funner with friends!Singleplayer is just as good as multiplayer, the same drive to survive is present, and so is the horror/creepy aspect.Worldgen isn't buggy at all, it is very good. Physics is responsible for anything... odd. But it's sensible.There is great variety in enemies, and so is there ways to deal with them. (Weapons, traps, and sneaking.)And I could go on about alot more, but I want you to appreciate the little things in this game yourself by playing. It really is worth what they are selling it for, and I couldn't blame them if they raise the price. I bought the two pack and I think it is worth it having a friend to play this game with. But singleplayer is just as fun too, and offers a great ""Would I make it alone if the world ended?"" simulation.In all honesty, this game is a way better version of Rust that is actually finished and has more unique and defining elements and mechanics to it that make you feel like you're actually playing a post-apocalyptic survival game where the world is actually out to get you. Compared to Rust you can also build better and easier, you'll actually come across zombies and loot, and multiplayer isn't proof that all humanity possesses an extra chromosome when thrown naked into the wilderness with a rock. If you bought Rust looking for what 7 Days to Die offers, demand a refund and reinvest the money here. You'll get a far far better game to play for years and years to come.TL;DR: I had to call my doctor after playing this game for more than four hours."
