76561198012071066,Recommended,251570,9821473,"Posted: 14 April, 2014",all,Thumb Of Doom,"I was leery about 7 days to die being another World War Z: An eager post apocolyptic survival game hashed together to profit off of a fad.But Every hour I play this game I get suprised by something the devs seem to have ""gotten right"".  I was impressed by the engine's support of below ground digging and mining.  I enjoy the crafting system as I look forward to being able to create the things I find by destroying it to create a mold.  The deterioration feels a bit fast but makes you consider when to fight and when to save your resources.The best part about the game occurs when the sun goes down.   I was shocked by how much of a threat the zombies become.  My first settlement was raised far off the ground so that I could shoot the zombies below with a crossbow.  As soon as the zombies noticed the source of the damage about 6 ""spider"" zombies scale the sides of my home and left me a bloody pulp up on the roof.Frequent bugs appear accross many elements of the game but none seem game breaking.  Keep in mind that it is early alpha.I love this game.  It's a survival horror that gives me more chills than I care to admit.  It has good atmoshpere, and more terrifying enemies than many games that like to call themselves horror/survival.It has a wonderful character about it halfway between minecraft and dayz.  The content is a bit limited at the moment but I look forward to wherever the devs take it.I'd classify the game primarily as a builder, and secondly as a shooter.  It should appeal to those who enjoyed Terraria, Starboun, and Minecraft but with a more enjoyable combat interface.I don't often find myself bored but when I do, I realize it's only due to my own lack of creativity.  At any rate, I'm never bored for long, as the next sunset is shortly on its way."
