76561197992704529,Recommended,251570,20004821,"Posted: 27 December, 2015",all,Milhouse Spring Break,"What can I say about 7 days? It largely depends on how you intend to play it.As a single player experience, it's tough, inconsistent and has no end-game play. Once you've firmly established a base you're pretty much done. You can keep challenging yourself through increased difficulty tweaks (the game has endless options for servers) but it's going to be largely the same game. Tweaks to the game's RNG have made survival very dependent on random chance, to say nothing of the little bugs here and there that still hamper gameplay. It's okay, I guess. It's harder than minecraft with a little less to do.As a persistant multiplayer experience ala Day Z or Rust, it's bad. Guns are very hard to acquire and most players I've found are very reluctant to engage in the no-holds-barred PvP that you see in a game like Day Z. If everybody cooperates against the environment it quickly trivializes any difficulty the game may have. It's entirely possible to build an impenetrable fortress before the first 7 day horde arrives at which point - why even bother?However, as a multiplayer experience played solely with one or two other people the game can be pretty satisfying; it maintains some of its single-player difficulty without being steamrolled under the heel of a dozen players rolling on the RNG. I think this is probably the best 7D2D experience.The game is still in early access and subject to change. A lot of the little things in the game that will nag at you have been in the game in some form through several builds and the game will continue to be semi-stable until release. Give it a try with a couple of friends, or don't bother; it's not really good unless you absolutely love minecraft style games and have to collect them all."
