76561198031973707,Not Recommended,251570,19824818,"Posted: 21 December, 2015",all,Eleazaros,"Don't be misled by that starting video - the game doesn't look much like that anymore - it's much nicer looking but with a harder to understand UI (screens you work with like inventory and crafting).Lots of neat concepts in this game - lots of highly questionable changes that add grind as 'game play'.Changes since that video:Lighting and atmosphere are much, much better and the art work and sounds - yes I'm one of ""those"" with a full surround sound system - are much better than before.  Models and such are a lot better done too and there are a lot of subtle changes to the sound effects in the game.Buildings, trees and such are better looking and more interesting (walk through trash on the floor and you may kick a can, etc.)  Environmentally it looks and feels better that what you'll see.Mocap - Motion Capture as in live humans doing the actions replayed as the animations.  Each to their own but 1920's style ""over acting"" isn't my forte.  Some will like  it but it looks way over the top to me as they grab their arm over dramatically and roar while doing a stiff legged stagger at you - things like that.Fighting zombies is nothing like shown - you aren't shooting a zombie in the face and it flops over dead unless you have ""skilled up"" a great deal.  Think of what you see more like being a top raider in the top end-game gear from a MMO -  and I do mean the best of the best gear possible to do what they are showing for combat.  (early game (day 2), 5 shotgun blasts to the face of a zombe and it still kept coming as I backed away - ammo isn't easy to get early on either and I had 8 of that kind coming at me [snow biome]).The body temp system needs work.  It is very unrealistic.  There is no way in hell anyone is going to clear 110 internal core body temperature and live -- I hit 112 on a cloudy day, wearing pants and a pair of grass shoes within the first 3 game-hours and I had water but ""wasn't thirsty""...It's very nice looking now but the costs in frame rates, tearing and such are annoying -- ""they'll fix that!"", eventually and probably break it again as they go further so the validity of complaining about performance vs looks... that's always going to happen as a game moves forward in development but the rest of it...The crafting and skill systems are old EQ1 / UO style approach to crafting and skilling up.  Read the newest guides, they are being designed to explain how you can work around the system until you get enough ""skill points"" to actually make/use things effectively.  Collect massive stuff, make huge batches of ""junk"" then you'll get something worth using - after a few hundred iterations...  Find ways to use tools and weapons where you are hidden/safe, then things work better.MASSIVE amounts of time-sinks in everything.  Forges now ""warm up"" materials so you can then wait for things to be made and using crafting stations summons zombies as the area ""heats up"" via the noise - and the UI has hit the skids big time...  That along with all the other timers that have gone in since they decided timers were needed...I hadn't played in a while but explaining general concepts to others would get them up and running ""back in the day"".  Now...  I couldn't figure out what the hell was going on with a forge the first time I made one - ""ok... fuel & materials - there's a recipe, ....  what's it doing?"" - it 'warms up'/preps the materials to then let you make stuff - so warm up batches first then make something?  And the value to actual playing is? ...Tons of icons pop up on the left side of your screen to show what your status is but important info doesn't show until it's getting pretty far along - like food and drink.  Injury and healing status - again it is ""granularized"" in such a way you'll need to learn what it's trying to tell you -- and I haven't bothered to find a consolidated info screen yet, due to all the screens it now has, but I'm fairly sure there is one burried in there somewhere that will give a full status overview.The UI is cludgey as hell to use and default keymappings are going to drive some a bit nuts.In otherwords, it's back to old-school style mass collection of crap, then figuring out how to AFK much of it in some practice mode until you can get the stuff/skills to actually do much of what you see in that older video - meanwhile later on, the whole thing does get easy - they just chose the ""rap up to god mode"" approach.Honestly it's not so ""tough"" as just tedious now and only those into old-school grindfests, with a ""pretty"" face lift, will probably find it all that engaging."
