,Recommended,251570,12027165,"Posted: 8 September, 2014",all,Ph.G.,"I rarely ever write reviews for titles that I purchase on Steam, but I have to make an exception for 7 Days To Die.  A little over a year ago this title was Alpha Version 1.0 - I purchased it around Alpha version 7.xx, and started playing extensively with Alpha version 9.0 and their release of procedural random world generation.  Three weeks ago.  It is now Alpha Version 9.2.This early access title is being aggressively and ambitiously developed.  The team is dedicated to making it the best experience it can be, and you can tell by how rapidly the versions have iterated in the past 12 months.  Hence this is one of the few Early Access titles that I feel very good about purchasing, and would recommend easily.As for the actual game itself:  Have you ever played Minecraft and just wished there was more *game* behind the creativity and exploration?  Have you ever wanted that Day Z experience, but with base construction and an interface that isn't extremely awkward?  You're looking at the perfect game to scratch those itches.I like to describe this experience in two separate ways.First:   7 Days to Die is ""Minecraft for Adults"".  The crafting and creativity aspects of the game come close to rivaling minecraft - and some would argue that it surpasses minecraft.  While the world is a fully destructible voxel world (blocks), the engine generates a mesh between natural blocks to make the world appear more smooth and realistic - it works very well, most of the time.  There are several types of materials you can craft with, upgradable blocks, and a growing list of doodads and decorative objects with lots of potential.  The game provides sloped, outer corner and inner corner block types of several varieties that can be rotated to many orientations before being placed, allowing a wide variety of interesting shapes and designs.  Not to mention, 7 Days actually features a rudimentary structural physics system - that's right, if your building is built poorly or out of the wrong materials, it can collapse, especially when hordes of zombies start pounding on it!Second:  This is the world's first Vietcong Simulator.  Scavenging is vital to survival, and you will eventually put together crappy, crude guns with salvaged scrap material.  You will dig holes filled with pungee sticks.  You will hide in dirt hovels, on the verge of starvation, waiting in ambush for an unsuspecting player to shoot them and steal their food.  You will craft handmade explosive traps out of scavenged car parts and candy tins that you will leave on the ground behind you in a desperate attempt to kill the bandits hunting you.  You will try to prevent people from detonating your house.  You will build underground bunkers and tunnels to hide and travel between locations unseen.  The PVP in this game is nothing short of intense - combat is lethal and unforgiving, and every action a player does will make a sound.  Opening your inventory, changing your weapon, applying a bandage, eating or drinking, looking at your map, ALL of it makes noise... and it can be heard both by zombies and other players.  PVP is using your ears and your brain to get the drop on your opponent, whilst being aware of your own noise levels and carefully sneaking to outmaneuver them.When I started playing this game with the Procedural World update, I had less than 5 hours in game.  All you need to do is look at my time played now to know exactly what I think of it.  I bought this instead of Rust or Day Z, and I couldn't be happier."
76561198134957172,Recommended,251570,24327119,"Posted: 14 July, 2016",all,C'est la vie,Nyaman
76561198062775309,Recommended,251570,23616244,"Posted: 17 June, 2016",all,Aryam,"I've been a player for years and this is my no. 1 position EVER! I love it! Game has REALLY few and not too sirious bugs for an Alpha. Heck, many final versions I played had more. But even if your new update has some I wouldn't worry, cuz the guys working on it are really great! They roll out updates like machines, make hotfixes within a DAY or TWO since new version bug reports. They add TONS of cool really climatic stuff in every version. The motions and physics keep getting better and better...The WORST thing I can say about this after almost 2 thousand hours is... It's got somwhat high requirements. :) Some games with comparable graphics (which are top notch) have visible advantage on hardware-performance efficiency... But that is perfectly normal for Alpha's and Beta's since, performance is usually the last thing you smoothen out before finishing a product... And this game is still growing.Extreme freedom, Incredible attention to detail... Constant fixes and upgrades. Like I said. Best game I played in my entire life AND it is still getting better!Buy 2-packs in bunches cuz multi is awesome as wel as single. Was worth every penny for me.OH! I love zombies (in a non-creepy way) but if someone doesn't... You can easily turn z's off which makes this a pure survival or PVP game! I also have to mention a huge freedom in settings. A great many aspects of a world you make are configurable and editable with an ingame menu.Just... Limitless freedom and realism. :)"
,Recommended,251570,23276848,"Posted: 29 May, 2016",all,VΛSID,"So I'm making this review specifically to counter the people saying ""They should work on polishing the features they put in instead of putting in new ones that break the game"". These people have no clue how programming works, or what an Alpha is. Polishing up exisiting systems is something you do in a Beta, not an Alpha. In an Alpha you're still adding in the systems planned out for the game, and each time you introduce a new one it's bound to break something, so while you squash bugs when you see them, the real focus in an Alpha is making all the systems, not polishing them. If you have a problem with buggy games and aren't just the type to deal with it and carry on, then don't buy the game until it enters it's Beta stage (or maybe even final release), period.Also if you think the dogs are impossible you need to seriously get good.Now for my real review:For me Minecraft, while a fun concept, always got boring because once I've built whatever lovely building or statue I wanted to build there was absolutely no purpose to it from then on other than my vanity. 7 Days to Die is amazing becuase it's harsh world and the 7th day hordes that come for you give you a damn good reason to build and maintain structures. Add to it the survival elements and other planned features and you have what in my opinion is already the best Zombie game ever made, and one that is frankly only getting better as they add more features. Once it's finished this game will be a monster.I've logged a long time with this game, playing both solo and with friends. It's a solid experience but it's clearly still being worked on so my recommendation is twofold: 1) only buy this game now if you can deal with bugs and your progress getting wiped every time a new major Alpha comes out. and 2) Keep in mind that as an alpha this game is a resource hog, so don't think that you can get by with the minimum specs. If your computer can't handle it or you don't want to deal with bugs then give this game a pass until it at least reaches Beta.Other than not being finished and having the bugs you'd expect from an Alpha, the game is quite fun, and even more so with friends so if you can get past it's current state I'd highly recommend it. Like I said though, when it's finished it will be amazing, so you might just want to wait for that as well."
