,Recommended,251570,11977738,"Posted: 4 September, 2014",all,UK(TZO)Saint,"7 Days to die is a perfect game for many people. Why is it so perfect? Because the developers let the gamer decide what kind of zombie apocalypse they want it to be. Will the zombies be the slow moving Romero kind. Or the fast moving 28 days later kind. Are days going to be short, or long? Will you enable air drops to not only help you, but possibly tempt you to your doom. How abundent will the loot be? Will you be finding ammo raining from the sky? Or will you be spending whole days just trying to find a jar of water? All of these things, the player decides, before the game even starts. When it does start however, you are thrown into a (possibly randomly generated world if you selected that world type :P ) where you will start with only a bottle of water and a can of chili, and a single bandage. The game gives you a 2 minute headstart, in this time you will be frantically searching for food, water, weapons, shelter, crafting materials. Then you see it... closing in over the hill, a zombie dedicated to hunting you down and eating your flesh. What do you do? Do you run over there and punch it with your bare fists? Or do you hide behind the rubble, or a tree, and pray he walks past you? Why not choose the third option. Using the advanced 5x5 crafting grid, get the ingredients and make yourself, and axe, or... possibly even a crossbow. When you find a house, is it just another looting oppertunity? Or will you board up the windows, lock the doors, create a moat of spiked traps around the house, or a concrete wall perhaps? The world never says; You must do this. The player decides what to do, and finds adventures in their own ways. Some may spend days chopping down tree's to make their dream cabin overlooking a lake. Others may spend days toiling the dirt ready for farmland. Some may spend days taking the fight to the walkers. The thing i love with this game, is there is no objective aside from survive. Do whatever it takes to see the sunrise again. Though i'm writing this review whilst it's still in alpha, i must say, the open world freedom, is remarkable, I have yet to find myself bored whilst playing this game. Sometimes it can be peaceful, and you forget the zombies are even there, when all of a sudden a horde of atleast 50 (no exaggeration) zombies will stumble across your house. The building mechanics are perfect for this kind of game, the crafting grid enables many recipes. The world contains many biomes, each will challange you in different ways. I could go on, but i think i'll leave this, with a 9/10 (and i'm sure it will get the other 1 after alpha is over :P)"
