,Recommended,251570,30743951,Posted: 25 March,all,Illeru,"Decided to tunnel under my base at night time because I was too scared to go out. Got comfortable to the repetitive zombie sounds outside.Died after 2 seconds when a zombie jumped on my head. Was mercilessly slaughtered for another 6 hours. 10/10 would do it again.7D2D is a remarkably challenging sandbox crafting and survival game. I enjoy being scared and also base building games, so thought it would be a bit of a hoot. I've spend a few days (IRL) trying to work out the best way to survive the horde - I think I would be one of the first to go if it happened for real. The basic mechanics are typical of a fp shooter/rpg type game, but it is rare to find a game where the crafting skills and inventory management play such a tactical role in your survival. I've really enjoyed the struggle, but if you aren't interested in that, creative mode or low difficulty settings might keep you occupied for a while.So a couple of comments/ suggestions/criticisms which might sway some people on purchase and might improve the game. Please note I do recommend this game if you feel aligned to the above comments:*Crafting elements are rather arbitrarily difficult to find recipies forThe RNG for finding the right plan for what you need is rather annoying. Then some of them are actually skills which you can spend experience on? An example of this is getting the workbench - then you can barely make anything worth while after 14+ days? I understand the option of doing building raids, but there should be another option for a turtle like myself who prefers to stay close to base, cautiously building up defences.*Building raids/skirmishing is prohibitively expensive for rewardThis may be my relative inexperience at this game, but I find myself stacking up a lot of arrows other consumables when trying to go hunting for recipies in prebuilt buildings. There is then next to no inventory space for looting multiple buildings if you are truly prepared... It is ""realistic"" but I don't want to spend all my time ferrying items back to my stash and waste another previous 7 day cycle for minimal item build progression.*Zombie sounds are repetitive and surround/3-D capability is poorThe sounds are fun/creepy, don't get me wrong, but it is rather tiring to listen to a horde bumbling around repetitively and incoherrently for 50 minutes straight while you wait for daytime. They should get excited if they break through one of your walls - or squeal when they die. Give me a reason to listen to it rather than put down the headphones! In that vein, if you are struggling to stay alive in pitch black (if you have ever tried it) you rather need some sense of direction - for which most people default to auditory senses. The distance/loudness balance is poor, with extremely loud sounds coming from zombies way too far away and panicking you for no reason. In some ways this is a complement to the atmosphere, but honestly it needs a lot of polishing. Similarly L/R balances are off too; it means you are much better off just doing a 360 spin and wasting some action time rather than being surpised when a zombie shows up on your blind direction.*Don't expect remarkable graphical effectsSpeaks for itself - it doesn't bother me;  go get mass effect if you want to push your graphics card.Summary:Its a great blend of elements, in a lot of games, to be a respectful representative of the zombie survival genre. It is lots of fun now, if you appreciate builders or survival games, play it. If you like zombie games, play it with headphones. I really hope this title gets the momentum it needs to get really polished up; the community is strong and it would be great for it to stay that way. ^^"
