76561198372449924,Recommended,251570,34647883,Posted: 31 August,all,Sovereign1MC,"Hello, fellow gamers! This is gonna be a bit of a long read! Before I bought the game, I had a lot of questions that made me worry about making the commitment, so I tried to be pretty detailed here to help those that are as ridiculously picky as I am! Hope this helps out, guys!Great game, so much of what I've been wanting in a single title!So, this is the first review I've ever posted for a game (except a couple that I did a long time ago on YouTube), but this one has earned it, and a positive one at that. Devs are active in supporting their players and continuing to improve the game. There doesn't seem to be any feeling that they are losing their interest here or have stopped putting their heart into it! In the simplest of terms, you may hear people say ""it's like Minecraft with better graphics and more adult-like."" And that is true, to a small extent, in the simplest of terms, and that is where the similarities end.You're dropped into a world, either the hand-crafted ""Navezgane"" or a randomly generated one full of all kinds of things great and small. You can level, learn new skills, harvest resources from trees, cars, building, cash registers, rocks, or dig right down into the earth. Not only can you harvest things from ANYTHING in the world, you can also search for loot (which is something us loot ♥♥♥♥♥s love) in cars, containers, refrigerators, bags, cupboards and so much more. There are zombies every step of the way, keeping things challenging (or not, depending on your preferences!), but never feeling over the top to the point that you have to stop what you're doing every second to take out more and more zombies that are now just bugging the crap out of you.There are sliders before entering your world allowing you to change overall general difficulty, how much or how little enemies spawn, loot spawning (such as making loot more or less richly dispersed around you), length of day/night cycle, length of in game day and so on. There are cheats, but I have never used them once so I can't detail what they are specifically, but I believe flying is one of them. Craft weapons from the resources you've gathered, as well as clothing and armor, find and assemble gun parts, once you have learned the appropriate schematic (or ""recipe"" as they call it), keep yourself hydrated, not too hot or too cold, and eat well. You can hunt for food and animal skins and can even use animal bones in crafting! It's possible to get diarrhea from eating or drinking questionable food items, sprain or break a leg (and then make a splint to heal it faster!), and so on. There is a great variety of zombies and other enemies to fight and in fact, I had taken a brief break from the game, around 3 months or so, and when I came back to it, there were several new enemies and some of the animals had been re-skinned and look even better, with a new animal added! Craft electric components like lights and powered doors, drawbridges, explosives, bullets - everything! For an alpha, this game is incredibly complete, but is still not even close to being complete; it's a weird thing to explain.There is a lot to keep you busy, as every 7 days, you are attacked by a horde of zombies when night falls (hence, the title). The hordes get progressively bigger and more difficult, but fear not! The game is NOT over once you die! That's something I was afraid of before I bought it. I thought that it was permadeath but it's not. In between each 7th day, you'll be working feverishly to stockpile ammo, guns, food, water, healing items, etc. and fortify your base, laying traps (yes! You can make traps!), building walls, bridges, steel doors and much more in preparation for ""Horde Night."" If you die frequently, the game scales back difficulty for you and if you go a long time without dying, the game ramps it up a bit. There are a good selection of diverse biomes to explore, each with their own unique threats and some have unique enemy types and resources as well, creating a great way to encourage you to actually explore, but why wouldn't you want to explore in an open world game anyway?!Find hidden bunkers underground, secret stashes and all kinds of goodies. This game has everything I've wanted in an open world game. There is Crafting, survival aspects such as eating, drinking, staying cool or warm enough, A LOT of buildable blocks to make your own awesome fortress, bunker, house, mansion, castle, or whatever you want, resource gathering, NPC's for trading ( added not too long ago!), guns, melee weapons, ZOMBIES, looting, free roaming and so on! You can even eventually cap out max health and stamina from 100 all the way to 200 from eating and drinking good, nutritional foods, but be warned, taking too much damage too often or dying will REDUCE your wellness! This game is AWESOME!! Get it now! Oh...and did I mention ZOMBIIIIIIIEEEESS!?My only main gripe with the game is that outside of constantly needing to gather resources and build your structures up stronger and stronger for the hordes, there isn't all that much to do. Again, what there is has been insanely entertaining and so much fun, but you may eventually find yourself being pretty powerful, so you might find that you don't NEED to go mining or scavenging for supplies, or build anything at the time. If and when this happens, there isn't much else to do at that point. Don't worry, you will sson face the horde and then have to get back to building and scavenging for the resources that you used in the fight and to repair broken traps or structures. I mean, you will always need to gather resources and build, but when you are where you need to be before the horde night comes and you have an in game day or two left, there isn't much else to do besides explore, which then leads to more scavenging ( which, again, is still very fun), but this leaves me wanting a change of pace. Some kind of minigames or something with a little variety would be fun.There are some ""missions"" or ""quests"" or whatever you want to call them, but they don't feel very ""fleshed out"" (pun intended). You can find written notes on zombies you've killed or in loot containers that give you some things to do. Things like ""kill X amount of Y"" or ""find this treasure chest"" can be fun the first 4 or 5 times you do them, but then again, you're left feeling like they are repetitive and pretty thin. I say AGAIN, that this by no means makes this game LESS better. I can still play for HUNDREDS of hours before I really find myself wanting something different to happen, but I WILL feel this way at some point when I have spent some time in a new world and have become pretty strong. Something to improve the more end-game content would be great, but in its current state, this game has more content and feels more complete to me than many AAA titles in recent years! That said, the graphics aren't great but are improved gradually through updates and there are various graphic settings that can still make the game look pretty good when set to ultra. I don't have a super powerful PC. It's a solid rig, to be sure. I have an Intel i7 6700K CPU @4.00GHz without overclocking, 16GB RAM and a Geforce GTX 1060 GPU and can run everything fine with settings at ultra. Occasionally I will get some frame drops and such when there is a lot going on or heavy particle concentrations, but it snaps out of it fast. If your PC can't handle these settings, there are many things to customize to make sure your rig can handle it. You can manually adjust lighting, god rays, particle effects, FOV, texture resolution, render distance and more for the ideal setup on your machine. Go and Pick this one up now if any of this sounds good to you. But it won't be good....it'll be great! Keep it up, Fun Pimps!"
