76561198017212892,Recommended,251570,8076400,"Posted: 16 December, 2013",all,Uncle Acid and the Deadbeats,"It's important to remember that this game is still in development, and therefore cannot be viewed as a complete product. There are lots of reviews littered around that complain about the lack of updates and features. I can't comment on those, but from what I have played, today, this game is a lot of fun and has a promising future. You begin with no supplys, and are expected to survive by crafting weapons and other materials from things you pick up. Basically the longer you survive, it seems, the more you can invest in your stronghold. After 3 nights, in one abandoned house, I felt unsure about leaving to get more supplys. I quickly found that leaving at night to get supplys is the equvilient to a big breasted girl running up the stairs in a horror movie. The usually cumbersome creatures that George A Romero directed in Night of the Living Dead, are replaced by raging meat sacks with more drive than teenage girls at a One Direction concert.The terrain is well designed, ranging from forested areas to city blocks and everything in between. It doesn't matter whether you prefer a small apartment or a wooden log cabin, you will find something that ticks the boxes. Ultimately, it doesn't matter because you will end up using metal sheets to board up the windows and doors. The white fence suburban areas have a really cool Walking Dead feel to them. I kept expecting to run into another player, with a patch over his eye and a sardonic grin on his face.The crafting system seems simple and easy to use, even for a mincraft novice like myself. The ease in which you find supplys is only rivaled by the totally unrealistic degradation of the weapons and (for some reason) doors. Within an hour of play time you will find yourself wielding a fire axe and chopping down the forest with the kind of rambunctious verve that would make the McDonald's corporation proud.The game, however, is not without its problems. Firstly, either the zombies in this game are all the reanimated corpses of structural engineers, or the devs need to tune down the damage they do against concrete blocks and metal slabs; I'm hoping for the latter because it gets really annoying constantly building new doors. At present, my work around is to just board up any openings with wooden blocks and hope they don't crash through. Secondly, and this is not the devs fault, but I would love to see another human being once in a while. When I was online, I was completely alone the entire time. I felt like the Omega Man, left to wander the earth with only my trusty dog (who had gone AWOL) and a bunch of shop mannequins for company. With more people online, this game could be a lot of fun. Imagine teaming up to keep out the zombie horde, or breaking down someone's barricade, just before nightfall, leaving them completely defenceless when it gets dark.It obvious that the development team behind this game are sitting on a potential goldmine. Zombies + Minecraft = a licence to print money. Yes it has some problems, but it's still in development. If you want a finished game, wait until it is released, next year. If you can't wait, however, this game is still a lot of fun in its current state. At $35US, it may seem a little steep, but compare that to the cost of most AAA titles nowadays and it's a bargain."
