76561198058803161,Recommended,251570,25415822,"Posted: 8 September, 2016",all,Kenny Loggins,"I bought this game a long time ago and I have played it on and off for years totaling 400 hours. I have not had the fortune to have people who want to play it with me in my small town, so i have had a mostly solo experience. I have played it through several patches and have seen the game progress through development.This is by far the best and most complete early access game I have ever played. I would say that it was worth $30 when I first got it many many patches ago. Now I think it is approaching full price marker ($40-$60) as they release new content. This game still does have some bugs, but rarely anything game breaking.The gameplay gets merit for the feeling of continual tension. As soon as you leave your base you are vulnerable, and sometimes even in your base you are. Zombies can and will evetually tear through anything, so you can never get complacent.The inventory, crafting, looting, and stats systems is very solid and still expanding. I feel a rush every time I find that perfect engine for my minibike or augur/chainsaw.All the compliments aside, my only real complaint is that the shooting system is a little clunky. I know this isnt halo, and perfect shootiing mechanics may make it too easy and remove some tension, but as I aim down my sniper scope, there will be times that I can not get the crosshairs to line up with the zoms at a distance. I know I am a bad shot, but when moving the mouse the smallest amount possible carries too much and I go back and forth without any possible shot (like the pixel where the zombie is standing is just not available) I get frustrated and leave out the range. Maybe I'm doing it wrong, maybe it is intentional, and maybe it just needs one more patch.Again, one of my favorite games ever and still getting better. Survivalcraft and it's absolute finest.Please release A15... I know you wont until it is done. Could you send someone to knock me unconscious until it is done, I tried holding my breath, but here I am"
