,Recommended,251570,24782266,"Posted: 8 August, 2016",all,Purps™,"So, first thing to get out of the way: I originally bought this game sometime in late 2014 or early 2015, a two pack for me and my bud, a process I call ""Forty Dollarsing"" where I buy into volatile online early access games for ♥♥♥♥♥ 'n giggles, named that way because most of them tend to be in the $20 price range.Most of the time I regret these purchases, but 2015 era 7 Days was the first one with so few redeeming qualities that I didn't even hit the refund timelimit. I refunded the game (and the gift copy, which is awkward to do), bought a CS:GO M4A4 skin and named it ""I refunded 7Days2die"". I still have the skin.http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=740128502I had the opportunity to try it again recently, having heard from a few sources that it'd been improved significantly, and immediately dumped around 9 hours on one session (on a different account to this one). The game is by no means perfect, it still has ups and downs, but it's definitely fun now. It performs around 400% better, the visuals are several times less likely to cause eye cancer and the progression and base building is addictive.There's a decent amount of things to commend the game for, but here's one that stands out against the slew of crap multi zombie survival games since Dayz: Fighting the AI doesn't suck ass. Yes, unlike multi-million selling titles Dayz and H1Z1, a modicum of effort was put into the melee combat portion of a game full of melee enemies. Rather than being lagmonsters that glide at you, deal damage and don't react to anything the zombies here actually react to where they're being hit, have actual attack hitboxes and serve as an actual obstacle in PvE beyond just being an annoyance. Thank ♥♥♥♥ing god. They're also numerous enough to be a threat (imagine that in a zombie game) and make clearing/exploring both the procgenned and prebuilt environments much more entertaining. They're the keystone of the experience that makes it more than just Minecraft with guns, turning it into the sort of game where you do everything with purpose: Building a cool fort not just because it looks cool, but also because it fills worthwhile ""Cool fort"" related functions like helping you not get torn to pieces.There's timesinks: games that you can put a lot of time into. Stuff like The Elder Scrolls and The Witcher.And then there's TimeS U C Cs: games that will absolutely suck you in and eat up all of your time. 7 Days to Die is a TimeS U C C."
76561198202794394,Recommended,251570,34803700,Posted: 7 September,all,Don't Touch Me I'm Christian,"Good with friends, sucks alone."
,Recommended,251570,13299089,"Posted: 9 December, 2014",all,MisterPete,"This game is way more fun than I was expecting, have already sunk it quite a few hours.  It's in a very playable state despite it being an alpha, wouldn't be disappointed even if this was the final state. Just a few minor bugs/annoyances mostly to do with inventory management.The simplest way to describe it is DayZ meets Minecraft but it is more realistic than Minecraft and less emphasis on weapons as DayZ. It's more about building up a base you can defend and getting your crafting up and running so that you can provide yourself with a steady source of food and water which are very important. In other words it is about survival with the constant threat of zombies.  Still a lot of fun to play even if you don't have the threat of other players and just play alone or co-op.The combat itself is not very deep.  Melee combat involves moving in to take a swipe with your crafted crude club or your sledgehammer and then backing out of range before the zombie lands a hit.  Rinse and repeat.  Still, it is pretty satisfying to head-shot a zombie with a crossbow bolt or a bullet from your rifle.  Weapons and ammo can be found or crafted.During the day zombies walk slowly and are not to difficult to avoid. At night you had better find refuge as the zombies start running and becoming more aggressive.  They will attempt to attack your home and knock the walls down so you are never truly safe.One nice touch is that when you are playing single player or running your own server you can configure quite a few options such as the number of zombies, amount of loot, length of night, whether the zombies run at night/day/neither, etc.Will you focus on building your own home and crafting or venture out and break into abandoned homes and loot them for goods? The choice is yours and will likely be a combination of the two.  You might even decide to take one of those abandoned homes as your own, reinforcing the windows and doors to withstand an attack.Lots of fun to play with friends."
