r to owning 7 days to die. One of the main reasons I did purchase this game was to support the early access developers.Perhaps, I am judging too harshly for an early access title, but maybe this game can change my mind in the future. I'd really like to enjoy this game. I'm honestly saying that this game may be impressive in the future. But not now."
,Not Recommended,251570,30199569,Posted: 26 February,all,wopolusa,"*If I could give this a 'meh' instead of a thumbs down I would* 7DtD is difficult to review. It has fun moments and is enjoyable to play with friends. But I would have to say it is still a ""bad"" game.In essence it's a strange cluster♥♥♥♥ of Minecraft, DayZ, Skyrim and virtually every early access zombie survival. Enjoyable to some extent but mechanically basic and unoriginal.Pro's:- Craft and manipulate almost anything you want to in the world on a block-by-block system (like Minecraft)- Edit everything you want about each playthrough - fine tune the difficulty and world settings any way you would like- Fun with friends- Relatively active developers (When I lasted checked anyway)- Performance friendly for an early access gameCon's:- Incredibly repetitive and slow, you have to put hundreds of hours into your character to get to the highest levels, most easily achievable by just repeating quick tasks for the attribute you want to level up (e.g. iron-dagger crafting from skyrim to level up)- Once you've hit the ceiling where you have done most things in the game it becomes less interesting very quickly.Subjective:- personally the multiplayer worked poorly and competitive multiplayer is basically a match of who can abuse game mechanics more than the next person.- The zombie survival genre is just not interesting to me anymore.Again its a difficult game to review, Tl:dr it's an unoriginal game with some really enjoyable moments to it.Overall 5/10"
,Not Recommended,251570,34527448,Posted: 27 August,all,Sparx419,"I rarely write reviews, but if you are considering buying this game, please read this; 4 years of development, with no end in sight.I may recieve a lot of flak for this, please, just keep in mind it is merely my opinion and I feel like sharing it with the 7DTD community.First lets start with this, the game has been in ""development"" for almost 4 years now, when really it hasn't been developed much at all. The problem lies in it's core. The Developers can't seem to focus on a single vision, and because of the the core, the foundation, of the game is in a constant state of flux.Now sure, one could argue they are improving it, but personally I liked the early versions. Between the minecraft style crafting and the simpleness behind it all. The problem is, changing the core of a game, uprooting and rearranging it's foundation, causes issues. They keep changing the core of the game, and are forced to then fix all the bugs that ensue, rather than continue development of the game, which I believe is one of the reasons there is such a large gap between updates. The concept is amazing and unique. A zombie survival game with terrain you can manage and it turns into a tower defense at night. Just reading the description is enough to get anyone excited, but a major part of the game, combat, is honestly just bad. The animations, hitboxes and general feel of the combat is uninspired at best. Combine that with the overall fairly poor graphics of the game and similarly poor performance, the game itself just feels uninspired.It has been 4 years, I have played every version, and honestly I feel the biggest content update to date has been the electronics. The game feels like it is in a perpetual state of ""Alpha"" with no end in sight for the actual release. Time that could be spent continuing the game is spent fixing bugs that wouldn't be there in the first place if they stuck with a single vision, and build around the foundation rather that trying to build the foundation around the game. 4 years, and no other major content updates come to mindNow don't get me wrong, I want to like the game, and honestly I did at one point. But now I feel like the game is being wasted. It has SO much potential, it could be so amazing, but the developers seem to be working excruciatingly slow and show very little work for it. I am not calling the game bad, just that if this cycle continues, I can easily see the game still in alpha in another 4 years. I understand building a game like this, especially with a team as small as theirs, can be time consuming and complitcated. But in 4 years the game hasn't progressed. They have merely changed the way crafting is done,  the UI, and a few other things a couple times over.The game IS still enjoyable though, especially for those fond of this genre. I just personally feel that with the money they have made, and the 4 years worth of time they have had, there should be more to show in the game.As stated above, this game's idea is amazing, unique, and interesting. But it's wasting it's potential by not fixing what really needs to be fixed.Please keep the flak to a minimum. As I said, this is my opinion and I felt like sharing it with the other people who do enjoy this game, or people like me who wish they could, but just cant in it's current state and with it's seemingly endless alpha cycle of changes."
