76561197972479524,Not Recommended,251570,34022201,Posted: 4 August,all,You Just Got Litt Up,"7 Days to Die is a decent game, however it seems to be headed in the wrong direction. The game has been in 'Early Access' Alpha for years now, and shows no signs of leaving any time soon. Even though it is still in development, there have been several major issues that have plaguing the game since the beginning.1.  There is no end game. You simply survive for the sake of surviving, and you build for the sake of building. You exist to exist, there's no purpose. Once you've reached the state where you have absurd amounts of home grown food, and in a zombie proof base (now with traps and turrets to kill zombies for you), you realize there's nothing to do and boredom sets in fast.2.  The grinding in the game is becoming a little bit silly. 7 Days to Die has always had some kind of grind to it - usually in the form of accumulating resources. However, the most recent versions of the game have introduced a levelling system featuring skill points and various skills. This was an exciting change originally, however since then it has been used as the main system to just add more and more grind. More and more things are being locked behind levelling, and the levelling itself gets slower and slower every update. The game essentially tries to keep you busy with a huge grind before you realize there is no end game.3.  Bad performance even on amazing computers. The Fun Pimps seem pretty adamant on cramming more and more crap into their game without ever taking a step back to optimize. I understand that in Alphas, you are supposed to create content and worry about performance later, but there comes a point where the current game infrastructure cant handle any more of the crap you keep throwing at it, and needs improvements. We've long since passed that point.4.  Poor difficulty. Game is pretty hard for new players due to lack of explanations and guidance. On top of this, the gameplay itself feels very floaty, and the visual/audio feedback doesn't help at all. Being slapped from 3 feet away by a zombie who winded up their attacks 3 seconds ago is a good indicator of what I'm talking about here. The game would prefer to kill you via Diahrea from eating a bad egg, than through a fair and challenging combat system.5.  Multiplayer. It sucks, and this explanation needs to be broken down.5a.  The current engine just isn't stable enough to support multiplayer in the way it needs supporting for a game of this type. The world size is so huge, yet servers still struggle supporting anything more than 32 players. Most servers begin to run extremely poor after 20 players are online. This makes for a huge world full of nobody, unless you like hanging around the spawn coordinates.5b.  There is no challenge in multiplayer, because the total count of zombies gets divided between all the players. To make this worse, because of server performance issues, zombie spawns are usually set to medium or low. This results in 20 zombies being divided amongst all connected players, meaning you hardly ever see a zombies in a game that is about... zombies...5c.  PvP is complete garbage. If you are one of those people who enjoy buying survival games because of PvP you will be poorly disappointed. 7 Days to Die caters entirely to players who have no jobs, no other hobbies, and are willing to invest most of their waking time to the game. Because the game is such a grind, it takes forever to get ""geared up"" in equipment that isn't complete trash, and compared to a player who hasn't put that time in yet, you are an unkillable god. I wish I were kidding, but things as basic as how far you gun can shoot are directly tied to level of loot you find, which is tied to your character level. A level 100 player who finds a sniper rifle will be able to shoot 250m with it, doing enough damage to 1 hit any player. A low level player who finds a sniper rifle will be lucky if he can even shoot 70m with it, and will require 3-4 shots to do the same amount of damage. However, since higher level players also have high level armor and ""armor skill"", they essentially have a multiplier on their health so a new player would actually have to shoot them 8-12 times.5d.  Duping. Duping make survival games pointless, and 7 Days to Die has had their share of dupe bugs in every single version they have released. Some have even gone on for years now. A duper can easily dupe garbage weapons, combine them together to get the quality to max, and then dupe the max quality weapon.Conclusion: Wait until the game is full released, or isn't still wearing this 'Alpha' tag. Right now there's no real reason to do anything that game requires, and with the game being such a grind and requiring such frequent restarts when a new patch drops, just makes for a huge waste of time and potential."
