76561198041111345,Recommended,251570,9695835,"Posted: 1 April, 2014",all,Mstblackrose,"I want to write this after looking through some of the other reviews or forum posts. I feel like there are a few things that need to be stated up front, so we're on the same page.This game is in Alpha phase testing. It is an early access game. If you do not respect that, or understand that, or acknowledge that, find another game to play for now. There will be bugs, changes, updates, improvements, and failures. You should not be looking at this game as a game to play that is release ready.You should acknowledge that, by buying into and playing an early access game, you are helping them test features and stability. If you find something you don't like about the game, you can and should tell the developers so they can assess that and decide if they agree with you or not. If you don't like the game as it is, help the devs make it into what you want it to be.That said, lets review the game.This game offers a sandbox playstyle. What that means to me and you might be different. What it means to the devs might be different from either of our ideas. What it means to me is that you choose how you want to play the game. The story isn't currently out yet. You don't get a lot of lore about what happened yet. You can guess though, by looking around the survival mode map. We'll see how it develops in time, but I am hopeful it will be fantastic. You can, however, build houses, towers, fences, traps, farms, weapons, and many more things. You can play with zombies or without zombies. You can play co-op with friends using their IP address and watching a quick youtube video if you can't figure it out or play on a dedicated server. You can turn friendly fire on or off to PvP. You can even be 'that guy' and run around in a co-op server destroying people's bases. Don't be 'that guy'.You can mine for sand to make glass, clay to make molds, stone to build with, metals for crafting, and even gunpowder.You can farm for food, provide water for crops, and protect them from zombies and wildlife alike.You can snipe zombies from a rooftop or mow them down with a chainsaw.Or you can do anything else the game physically allows you to do. It is your sandbox so play it the way you want to.The world is fairly open, too. Sure there are borders to the world where you die from radiation poisoning if you leave it, but the game is in Alpha. They are testing physics, AI, crafting, balance, stability, lag, etc. They are not currently, as of 7.7, testing random world, near infinite borders, etc. It would be lovely if at some point this game map got to be the earth and you could travel the globe, but how big would the game need to be to basically be Google Earth + zombies? Is that even reasonable? We'll see how it goes.There are multiple ways to make the game easier or harder as you play. There is a loot timer option, which allows you to determine if you want to stand still and actually open boxes and treasure corpses, adding realism, or if you want to make it instant so you can loot on the run. You can set block durability higher or lower, that is, the blocks in the game that you beat up or build with, so that they are easier or harder to destroy. You can set your damage and zombie damage so that it is nearly impossible to kill a zombie but they can one shot you or you can mow down hordes with your bare hands but they barely scratch you. You can change the length of day cycle and night percent to make more day per day and less night per night. You can TEST the game.I find more often than not, for the first few days of game play I run really long days with 20% night, then at night I exit the game and set the day cycle super short, wait for morning to come a minute later, then reset the day length really long. Will I be able to do that at the games actual release? Probably not. I have been experimenting with different base designs. Based on where I start on the map, since there ARE multiple first day spawn locations, I either gather stones and build a tower on stilts, take over a pre-existing house, or make myself something to dig with and start making a tunnel. I work on securing a food supply and water supply as quickly as possible through farming and rivers/lakes, and I work on testing areas and features. If I find something I think needs to be tweaked, changed, updated, or removed, I am free to mention it on the forums. This is what an Alpha phase is for. If you approach it like that and play it for fun, knowing full well that the features present today may be different in a few weeks, whether updated or removed, you will love this game.Have fun with it. The game isn't complete. You get to help make it complete. What are you really getting out of it for you money? Why should you have to pay them to help make their game? Because not everyone who has a good idea has enough money to spend a year or two doing nothing but building a game that may or may not take off. Because finished or not, it's still fun and playable and enjoyable if you approach it with the right mindset. Oh, and because it's quite likely going to be cheaper than buying it later when it is at full release."
