,Recommended,251570,10330770,"Posted: 2 June, 2014",all,rhoms,"That was unexpected; this statement is what I can best say to describe my experience with 7 Days to Die so far. It was unexpected that it would be so good. It was unexpected that it would be so much fun to fight off zombies in what seemed to be just another zombie survival game. It was unexpected that I would find a surprisingly deep game in something that is otherwise bland at first glance.If 7 Days to Die nails one thing right away, it's atmosphere. While the graphics look relatively unflattering, to be kind, and the frames can drop down to awful at times, the game draws you in with the fear of the undead peering at you through their sunken eyes. The zombies are downright scary to deal with in the beginning, but it only amps up in intensity when you have to fight off hordes of them. That's right, hordes. They pour around the buildings, shuffling around in a rhythmic advance, while you crouch beneath your shattered staircase holding your breath despite yourself. The fact that their awareness is through the smell of the items such as food that you carry in your backpack and your toolbar, and the fact that they can indeed hear you just adds to the intensity of the game.I could go on for a good while about the pros and cons about the game, but I'll wait for the full version to be released. As of now, FPS drops and some poor game mechanics bog down an otherwise good game destined for greatness in future updates. Is it DayZ? No. Is it Minecraft? No. Is it something you've seen before but somehow special? Yes. 7 Days to Die proves itself as one of the most promising Early Access titles currently available on Steam today."
